<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 1600 GMT, September 24 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW -- Russia Thursday welcomed the United Nations Security
Council resolution on the issue of Kosovo, Yugoslavia, the
Interfax news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The Foreign Ministry said in a news release that "there is no
reasonable alternative to a peaceful settlement in Kosovo."
</P>
<P>
The U.N. resolution adopted Wednesday calls for a negotiated
settlement of the conflict between official Serb forces and ethnic
Albanians in the southern Yugoslav province.
</P>
<P>
While calling for Kosovo to stay within the Yugoslav
federation, it demands extensive autonomy for the province.
</P>
<P>
The Russian ministry said the U.N. resolution introduced no new
sanctions against Yugoslavia, and gave no green light for the use
of force demanded by some members of the U.N. Security Council.
(Russia-UN-Kosovo)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BRUSSELS -- NATO issued on Thursday an activation warning for a
limited air strike and a phased air campaign in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
The warning allows NATO to enter into a state of increased
level of military preparedness and to identify the assets required
for the planned military actions, said NATO Secretary-General
Javier Solana in issuing the warning.
</P>
<P>
Solana said: "The use of force will require further decision
by the North Atlantic Council.
</P>
<P>
"But the decision is an important political signal of NATO's
readiness to use force if it becomes necessary to do so."
</P>
<P>
He also expressed strong support of the U.N. Security Council
resolution adopted on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
NATO has been studying various options of the use of force in
the Yugoslav province of Kosovo ever since NATO foreign ministers
met in late April. (NATO-Kosovo-Warning)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
ISLAMABAD -- Iran will keep its troops at its eastern border
with Afghanistan, "as long as it feels insecure," Iranian
Ambassador to Pakistan Mehdi Akhundazdeh said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
He told reporters at a press conference, "Our troops would
remain there to safeguard our national integrity against growing
cross-border drug trafficking, but their posture will remain
defensive."
</P>
<P>
He said some 400 Iranian security troops, including a senior
commander, have been killed in clashes with drug traffickers at
the Iran-Afghan border over the past year.
(Pakistan-Iran-Afghanistan) 
</P>
</TEXT>
