<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Security Council Holds Ministerial Meeting on Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 24 (Xinhua) -- The U.N. Security
Council Thursday convened the second ministerial Meeting on
Africa to gather more international efforts to bring peace,
stability and development to the conflict-torn Africa.
</P>
<P>
Foreign ministers from the 15 Security Council member states,
including Chinese Foreign Minister Tang Jiaxuan, were present at
the meeting, which was held on the sidelines of the 53rd General
Assembly session.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the meeting, U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan said
that the Security Council has showed its commitment to lasting
peace in Africa by setting up active working groups and adopting
very important resolutions on recommendations of a report
submitted by Annan in April, and by authorizing two new
peacekeeping operations -- in the Central African Republic and in
Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
The report, also to be considered by the General Assembly in
October, emphasized that any and all efforts at securing peace
have to be combined with steps towards ending Africa's poverty.
</P>
<P>
Specifically, the report, seen as one of the most important
reports by Annan since he came to office last year, called for the
promotion of investment and economic growth, ensuring of adequate
levels of international aid, reduction of debt burdens and opening
of international markets to Africa's products.
</P>
<P>
In the speech, Annan called upon the international community to
encourage investments in Africa, to consider converting all
remaining official bilateral debt owed by the poorest African
countries into grants, to increase the volume and improve the
quality of official assistance to Africa, and to ease access
conditions for African exports.
</P>
<P>
Africa "has largely been marginalized in the process of
globalization," Annan said.
</P>
<P>
The ministerial meeting was held at a time when gun shots had
been fired between Ethiopia and Eriteria, in the Great Lakes
region and West Africa.
</P>
<P>
"The United Nations, in partnership with the OAU (Organization
of African Unity) is actively involved in seeking an end to every
one of these crises and to alleviate the suffering borne by
innocent people," Annan said.
</P>
<P>
"But in a large sense, we can only appeal to the wisdom and the
responsibility of leaders to put the interests of their people
over their own," he added.
</P>
<P>
The ministerial meeting on Africa is expected to adopt a
presidential statement, which will reaffirm the Security Council's
commitment to Africa in the areas of conflict prevention and the
maintenance of international peace and security. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
