<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New 20-Dollar Bill Enters Circulation in U.S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 24 (Xinhua) -- A redesigned 20-dollar
bill, believed to be harder to counterfeit, entered Thursday into
nationwide circulation in the United States.
</P>
<P>
The Federal Reserve's 12 regional banks have begun shipping two
billion new notes, totaling 40 billion dollars, to the nation's
banks, savings institutions and credit unions.
</P>
<P>
The old 20-dollar note will remain legal tender, said Treasury
Department officials at a ceremony. And the Fed will circulate
the old notes until they wear out, on average in two years.
</P>
<P>
After six months, one in every four 20-dollar bills in
circulation are expected to be of the new design, which
incorporates a range of features intended to frustrate
counterfeiters armed with personal computers, scanners, ink-jet
printers and color copiers.
</P>
<P>
The new note is the third of the Series 1996 to be redesigned
with new anti-counterfeiting features.
</P>
<P>
The most obvious change is the larger and off-center portrait
of Andrew Jackson, the nation's seventh president, on the bill's
face. The reverse features a picture of the north side of the
White House, instead of the south side seen on the old notes. To
help people with poor vision, the bill's denomination appears in
large dark numerals on a light background.
</P>
<P>
The government issued new 100-dollar notes, with Benjamin
Franklin, in March 1996, and new 50-dollar bills, with Ulysses S.
Grant, in October 1997. It plans to issue new 10-dollar bills and
5-dollar bills simultaneously in 2000 and a more modestly
redesigned one dollar bill after that.
</P>
<P>
The newly-circulated bills have a watermark in the shape of a
portrait, visible when the bills are held to a light, and an
embedded plastic security thread that glows under ultraviolet
light, red for the 100-dollar bills, yellow for the 50-dollar
bills and green for the 20-dollar bills.
</P>
<P>
The numeral in the lower right corner of each denomination's
face is printed in color-shifting ink. It looks green when viewed
straight on and black when viewed from an angle. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
