<HEADLINE> Zhang Wannian Stresses Sino-Japanese Ties in Tokyo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, September 24 (Xinhua) -- Japan should look at history in
a right perspective and handle the Taiwan issue properly, Zhang
Wannian, Vice Chairman of the Central Military Commission of
China, told Japanese defense officials Thursday.
</P>
<P>
In a meeting with Director-General of Japan's Defense Agency
Fukushiro Nukaga, Zhang said Sino-Japanese relations are generally
good despite the ups and downs since the two countries normalized
their diplomatic ties 20 years ago.
</P>
<P>
On the proposed new guidelines for Japan-U.S. defense
cooperation, he said it would help ease China's concerns over the
Japan-U.S. program if Japan could clarify that the scope of the
new guidelines did not cover China's Taiwan province.
</P>
<P>
Zhang reiterated that carrying the Sino-Japanese friendship
from generation to generation is not only in the fundamental
interests of the two peoples, but also conducive to the peace and
stability of the Asia-Pacific region and the world at large.
</P>
<P>
Nukaga welcomed Zhang's visit to Japan and agreed that
maintaining a sound Japan-China relationship is very important.
</P>
<P>
The Japanese defense chief hoped that personnel exchanges
between the two countries' armed forces should be further
enhanced. 
</P>
</TEXT>
