<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Scottish Lockerbie Lawyer Raps Libyan Decision </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 24 (Xinhua) -- A Scottish lawyer acting for
two Libyan suspects accused of undertaking the 1988 Lockerbie
bombing Thursday launched verbal attacks upon Libya's decision to
name a new defense team.
</P>
<P>
Alister Duff was quoted by Reuters as saying Thursday that he
had been shocked by the Libyan decision to appoint former Libyan
Foreign Affairs Minister Kamal Maghour to lead the defense team
and expressed concern over this action.
</P>
<P>
"I am very concerned about this. It can be argued that the
Libyan establishment has interests which conflict with those of
the accused. We have to be very concerned about Libya's motives,"
Duff said.
</P>
<P>
"The accused might find the advice they are given by the new
team is colored by the Libyan authorities' views. I didn't expect
this at all. It's ghastly, to be frank," he said.
</P>
<P>
This latest development of the Lockerbie case could cast
further doubts on whether the two suspects could be put on trial
in The Hague, the Netherlands, before a Scottish court.
</P>
<P>
Some 270 people were killed when a Pan AM flight 103 exploded
over the Scottish town of Lockerbie in December 1988. The British
and American governments have been locked in heated arguments with
Libyans on how to stage a trial for the two Libyan suspects.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
