<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hosts Dominates Opening Day at China Cup Gymnastics </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIANJIN, September 24 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese gymnasts took no
sweat to sweep all four titles on offer in the first day of the
China Cup International Gymnastics Tournament here on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Both team and all-round individual titles easily went to C
hina, who sent three teams to compete in the tournament which
could hardly claim to be a showcase of the world's best with no
Russians present and other participating countries and regions
apparently fielding none of their first-string line-ups.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese men's team A, led by Good Will Games champion
Huang Xu, captured the team gold with 172.55 points, with
hosts'team B following up with 169.50 and Belarus the third with
165.30.
</P>
<P>
The women's team events were aslo dominated by the host
gymnasts, while their team A scoring 114.512 points to lead a
1-2-3 finish for the host nation.
</P>
<P>
All-round competition seemed to be a domestic battle between
the Chinese athletes. Huang Xu held off strong challenges from
teammates Zhao Sheng and Yang Wei to snag the well-earned gold
with 57.800 points. Zhao and Yang came on second and third with
57.725 and 57.575, respectively.
</P>
<P>
Eight of the top 10 finishers on the women's all-round
individual table come from the host nation. A relatively unknown
Rao Meizhen notched up 38.512 points to steal the gold from world
cup champions Liu Xuan and Kui Yuanyuan.
</P>
<P>
The only non-Chinese gymnast on the awarding podium was twice
French national champion Elvire Teza, who managed 38.012 points
to finish eighth. 
</P>
</TEXT>
