<HEADLINE> S. Africa, Mexico Sign Cooperation Agreement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, September 24 (Xinhua) -- South Africa and Mexico
signed a cooperation agreement in New York on Wednesday night,
South African Foreign Ministry said in a statement Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The agreement, signed by South African and Mexican foreign
ministers, Alfred Nzo and Rosario Green, was intended to
strengthen cooperation in the political, economic, technological,
educational and cultural fields, the statement said.
</P>
<P>
South African Foreign Minister Alfred Nzo described the accord
as "an important landmark in the relations between the two
countries."
</P>
<P>
"The two ministers reaffirmed their like-minded positions on
nuclear disarmament, landmines and the illicit trafficking of
small arms and light weapons and pledged to continue their close
cooperation on these issues in the various multilateral fora,"
said the statement.
</P>
<P>
The statement also said Green would visit South Africa in
early 1999 and South African Deputy President Thabo Mbeki, Nzo
and Trade and Industry Minister Alec Erwin would visit Mexico.
</P>
</TEXT>
