<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-24 16:55 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Jordanian Government Wins Parliament's Confident </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Twelve lawmakers voted against the 23-member cabinet led by
Prime Minister Fayez Tarawneh, two abstained and one was absent.
The speaker of the House does not need to participate
in the voting according to the Constitution, the Petra said.
</P>
<P>
The vote was conducted after the Lower House finished three-day
heated debate on the new government`s policy statement.
</P>
<P>
With the vote of confidence, the House members hoped that the
government will live up to its promises outlined in the policy
statement to combat corruption, unemployment and poverty.
</P>
<P>
They also called on the government to slow down efforts to
normalize ties with Israel under the peace treaty between the two
countries and focus on upgrading ties with Arab states.
</P>
<P>
They noted that Jordan`s ties with Arab states have been
harmed by the kingdom`s peace treaty with Israel and need to be
enhanced.
</P>
<P>
Tarawneh Thursday delivered a speech in response, saying that
his government will do its best to fight against corruption, curb
unemployment and combat poverty.
</P>
<P>
Tarawneh`s cabinet, which was appointed by King Hussein on
August 20, a day after the previous government resigned, includes
many technocrats and was shouldered with the major task of
curbing unemployment and poverty and in effect reviving the
kingdom`s economy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
