<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Expelled Lesotho Army Chief Reinstated </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, September 24 (Xinhua) -- Lesotho army chief
Lieutenant-General Makhule Mosakeng, forced to resign at gun
point by mutinous soldiers, resumed command of the Lesotho
Defense Force (LDF) Thursday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
Lesotho Prime Minister Pakalitha Mosisili said Mosakeng and
the more than 60 senior officers who fled to neighboring South
Africa during the mutiny, which began on September 11, would
resume their positions immediately, South African Press
Association (SAPA) reported.
</P>
<P>
"The commander, Lt-General Mosakeng, and senior management
will work in close cooperation with the commanding officers of
the intervention forces from Botswana and South Africa to restore
the command structure in the army and in the country as a whole,"
Mosisili reportedly told the state-controlled Radio Lesotho.
</P>
<P>
Mosakeng told reporters that he had been forced to resign and
that his resignation was not valid. Only King Letsie III had the
power to accept his resignation. He said he was therefore still
commander of the LDF. 
</P>
</TEXT>
