<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Palestinians to Go Ahead With Statehood Plan at </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, September 24 (Xinhua) -- A senior Palestinian
official has said that Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat will not
reverse his plan to announce at the U.N. the intention to declare
an independent state next May.
</P>
<P>
"Arafat will not change a single word in his speech on this
issue and let the members of the General Assembly to judge who is
against the peace process," said the official in Gaza Thursday,
who spoke on condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
The words came as Israeli leadership is trying to advise Arafat
not to announce his statehood plan when addressing the General
Assembly on October 2.
</P>
<P>
Israel has repeatedly warned that if the Palestinian National
Authority (PNA) declares a state next May, it will take tough
actions against the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu, who is in New York
attending the General Assembly, renewed his opposition Thursday
when meeting with U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright.
</P>
<P>
He said that the creation of an independent state will mean
gains for the Islamic Resistance Movement (Hamas) terrorism.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu asked Arafat not to try to gain diplomatic support at
the U.N. for this purpose.
</P>
<P>
Israeli President Ezer Weizman and opposition Labor party
Chairman Ehud Barak also echoed Netanyahu's stance, asking Arafat
not to stage diplomatic activities or lobby the U.N. support for
his statehood campaign.
</P>
<P>
Barak said the PNA and Israel can reach an agreement on troop
redeployment and move onto the final-status talks, but he did not
say how.
</P>
<P>
Weizman said the announcement to declare an independent state
can cause more dangers to the peace process.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinians and Israel are haggling over a U.S. proposal
on Israeli troops withdrawal from the West Bank, and no tangible
progress has been made so far.
</P>
<P>
Israel's thwart and threat also met rebuttal from other
Palestinian officials.
</P>
<P>
Palestinian chief negotiator Saeb Erekat said "we can not work
as guards on lips of Mr. Netanyahu and we hope that Netanyahu to
refrain from using statements of threats, war and re-occupation,"
the Voice of Palestine reported.
</P>
<P>
PNA Cabinet Secretary Ahmad Abdel Rahman said Thursday that
Israel is conducting military trainings to raid Palestinian cities
in order to frighten the Palestinian people to halt its national
plan of declaring an independent state.
</P>
<P>
"This is a psychological war and nerve war, but Israel should
think a thousand times before they take any aggressive measures
against the Palestinian people," he said.
</P>
<P>
"There will be no chance for Israeli extremists and
expansionists to move the clock needles backward, Palestinian
existence is a reality and is not a charity from the Netanyahu
government," he stressed.
</P>
<P>
He said the declaration of the Palestinian state is in
accordance with the Oslo accords and the international law.
</P>
<P>
The Oslo accords, which kicked start the peace process in 1993,
envisage that an independent Palestinian state will be created
when a five-year transient period ends in May 1999.
</P>
<P>
"Israel should commit to what is stipulated by the agreements
and their non obligation will mean that the entire world will
unanimously stand by the Palestinian people to face Israel," he
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
