<HEADLINE> Lesotho King Barred from Speaking on Radio </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, September 24 (Xinhua) -- Lesotho King Letsie III
was Thursday barred by the government from speaking to his nation
through state-controlled Radio Lesotho.
</P>
<P>
The country's Information and Broadcasting Minister Mnyani
Mphafi told local radio reporters that whatever was to go on air,
including the king's message, had to be approved by the
government, in particular, by Prime Minister Pakalitha Mosisili,
South African Press Association (SAPA) reported.
</P>
<P>
Mphafi returned the statement to the king, who then sought
Mosisili's intervention, said SAPA.
</P>
<P>
The king's secretary returned to the palace with news that
Mosisili had refused to allow the king to speak.
</P>
<P>
In the prepared address, the king appealed to the Lesotho
nation to be calm, take stock of what had happened and put aside
their differences in a quest to normalize the nation, according
to SAPA.
</P>
<P>
Opposition parties reacted angrily to the Lesotho government's
censoring the king, SAPA said.
</P>
<P>
Mphafi also told Radio Lesotho employees and reporters to stay
at home until advised otherwise.
</P>
<P>
"As you know the station has not officially been opened and
for security reasons it will be best for you to stay at home
until you are told to return to work.
</P>
<P>
"Only a few of you will be asked to come to work," Mphafi
said.
</P>
<P>
Some employees reacted angrily to Mphafi's remarks, saying
those who had been chosen to come to work were aligned to the
ruling Lesotho Congress for Democracy.
</P>
<P>
The station was closed last week following a blockade of its
entrances by opposition supporters. 
</P>
</TEXT>
