<HEADLINE> Taliban Charge D'affaires Leaves Saudi Arabia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, September 24 (Xinhua) -- Expelled Afghan Taliban
Charge D'affaires to Saudi Arabia Mawlawi Shehab Eddine Dalawer
left Riyadh Thursday for home, with the Taliban's embassy still
working, the Kuwait News Agency (Kuna) reported.
</P>
<P>
This was confirmed by Abdelwahab Moulawi Said, first secretary
at the Taliban's embassy in Riyadh, during a telephone interview
with Kuna.
</P>
<P>
Abdelwahab said Dalawer's departure "was to implement the Saudi
government decision on recalling its charge d'affires from Kabul."
</P>
<P>
Saudi Arabia on Tuesday recalled its charge d'affaires from
Afghanistan and asked the Taliban charge d'affaires in Riyadh to
leave the country "in keeping with national interests."
</P>
<P>
Saudi Arabia is one of the three countries that have recognized
the Afghan Taliban government.
</P>
<P>
In response to a question on whether the Saudi decision is
related to Afghanistan's harboring Osama Bin Laden, a Saudi
dissident whose nationality was evoked years ago, Abdelwahab said
he "did not know the real reason, but believed it could be related
to the decision."
</P>
<P>
He stressed that the Taliban government would "do its utmost to
improve relations with Saudi Arabia and remedy any problem
standing behind the Saudi stance."
</P>
<P>
Saudi Arabia's move also came amid a worsening tension between
Iran and the Taliban militia which kidnaped 10 Iranian diplomats
and reporter in northern Afghanistan on August 8 and later killed
eight of them.
</P>
<P>
Abdelwahab said that the Afghan charge d'affaires left Riyadh
along with his family aboard the Saudi airlines.
</P>
<P>
The diplomatic representation between Saudi Arabia and Taliban
started in May, 1997, following Riyadh's diplomatic exchange with
Kabul which did not exceed the level of charge d'affaires.
</P>
<P>
Abdelwahab reiterated the Taliban regime and Afghan people's
appreciation for the Saudi leadership, saying "we consider Saudi
Arabia as elder brother for us and to all Islamic countries." 
</P>
</TEXT>
