<HEADLINE> UK Sees Building Africa's Peace as Its Diplomacy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 24 (Xinhua) -- Britain would make it
the priority of its diplomacy in Africa to build peace and prevent
conflicts, Britain said here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the Second U.N. Security Council Ministerial
Meeting on Africa, Robin Cook, Secretary of state of foreign and
commonwealth affairs of Britain, said his country would support
the Organization of African Unity in its peacekeeping initiatives
to develop Africa's own capacity for peacekeeping.
</P>
<P>
Cook said Britain would fund the process of rebuilding peace
where war had destroyed it and urge the international community to
join its efforts in this essential task.
</P>
<P>
Britain would be responsible in its own policy on the export of
arms and would not allow its sales to fuel other countries'
conflicts as well as support initiatives to control the trade in
small arms and to stamp out the illicit market in fire arms, Cook
noted. 
</P>
