<HEADLINE> U.S. Grants COMESA $5.2m for Peace Keeping </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, September 24 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. government has given
the Common Market for Eastern and Southern Africa (COMESA) a
grant of 5.2 million U.S. Dollars to strengthen Africa's capacity
to deal with conflicts on the continent and promote economic
growth.
</P>
<P>
COMESA's Secretary-General Erastus Mwencha said in an
interview here Thursday that 2.1 million dollars of the grant
would be used to fund activities aimed at promoting peace and
resolving conflicts in Africa, according to Zambia News Agency
(ZANA).
</P>
<P>
While the remaining 3.1 million Dollars, said Mwencha, would
be used to implement a detailed partnership program for economic
growth between the U.S. and the 20-member regional grouping.
</P>
<P>
The COMESA chief, who did not say when the grant was given,
explained that the partnership program being embarked on would
seek to remove impediments to local and foreign investment in the
sub-region.
</P>
<P>
He added that the partnership program also included the
improvement of telecommunication to enhance trade among COMESA
members.
</P>
<P>
The COMESA, which originated from the Preferential Trade Area
for Eastern and Southern Africa in 1994, aims to achieve a full
free trade area by the year 2000, a customs union with a zero
tariff on products originating within the common market as well
as a common external tariff.
</P>
<P>
It now has 20 members including Angola, Burundi, the Comoros,
Egypt, Eritrea, Ethiopia, Kenya, Lesotho, Madagascar, Malawi,
Mauritius, Mozambique, Namibia, Rwanda, Sudan, Swaziland, Uganda,
the Democratic Republic of Congo, Zambia and Zimbabwe.  
</P>
</TEXT>
