<HEADLINE> Security Council Calls for Peaceful Solution in Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 24 (Xinhua) -- The U.N. Security
Council Thursday ended the second ministerial meeting on Africa
with the adoption of a presidential statement, urgently calling
upon African countries and all parties concerned to demonstrate
the political will to settle their disputes by peaceful means.
</P>
<P>
The Security Council expresses its continuing concern over the
number and intensity of conflicts in Africa, and especially at the
emergence of new conflicts during the past year, the statement
said.
</P>
<P>
The Security Council encourages states in the region to
continue to improve the implementation of good governance and
undertake the various reforms needed to promote economic growth,
the statement said.
</P>
<P>
The meeting, involving foreign ministers from the 15 Security
Council member states, was held on the sidelines of the ongoing
53rd General Assembly session. Chinese Foreign Minister Tang
Jiaxuan took the floor at the meeting to express China's views on
peace, stability and development in Africa.
</P>
<P>
The presidential statement called upon the international
community to assist those efforts initiated by African states and
regional and subregional organizations to introduce lasting peace
and sustainable development into Africa.
</P>
<P>
The Security Council recognized that "the challenge of
achieving peace and security in Africa is a continuous process,"
and it will continue to assess progress in promoting peace and
security in Africa at the level of foreign ministers on a biennial
basis, the statement said.
</P>
<P>
The first ministerial meeting on Africa was held on September
25, 1997. 
</P>
</TEXT>
