<HEADLINE> Russia Tells Clinton it Opposes Force in Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 24 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill
Clinton was told by Russian Foreign Minister Igor Ivanov during a
meeting Thursday that Russia opposes the use of force to end the
violence in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
Following their meeting at the White House, Ivanov told
reporters that his country opposes military strikes to end the
bloodshed in the Yugoslav province.
</P>
<P>
"Use of power, irrespective of where it comes from, cannot
bring about the resolution of the Kosovo problem," the foreign
minister said.
</P>
<P>
"Any power action can only lead to unpredictable consequences
and this is something that cannot be allowed to happen," he said.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. Security Council Wednesday demanded a cease-fire and
urged Serbs to negotiate with Kosovo Albanians, who seek
independence.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO)
Thursday began preparing for possible military intervention to
halt a Serbian offensive which has made tens of thousands of
ethnic Albanian civilians homeless.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. has indicated that it does not need to be approved by
the U.N. Security Council to use force against Yugoslavia in the
province. 
</P>
