<HEADLINE> IMF Approves Stand-By Credit for El Salvador </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 24 (Xinhua) -- The International Monetary
Fund (IMF) Thursday announced the approval of a stand-by credit
for El Salvador in an amount of about 52 million U.S. dollars to
support the government's 1998-99 economic program.
</P>
<P>
The government of El Salvador expressed it intent to treat the
credit as precautionary.
</P>
<P>
The government's program for 1998-99 aims to maintain
sustainable high rates of growth, while containing inflation.
</P>
<P>
The program is targeted at a rate of GDP growth of 4 percent in
1998 and 4.5 percent in 1999, which is predicated on the
assumption that the turmoil in international markets does not have
a significant adverse effect on the country's exports or
investment in 1999.
</P>
<P>
Inflation is expected to be contained at about 3.5 percent in
1998 and 3 percent in 1999 and net international reserves are
expected to increase to the equivalent of seven months of imports.
</P>
<P>
El Salvador joined the IMF in March 1946. Its quota is about
172 million dollars. It has no outstanding use of IMF credits so
far. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
