<HEADLINE> Clinton, Saudi Crown Prince Meet on Gulf Security </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 24 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill
Clinton and Saudi Crown Prince Abdullah are meeting here Thursday
over the security in the Gulf and the Middle East peace process.
</P>
<P>
"It will range across all those issues that the United States
and Saudi Arabia work together on: combating terrorism, supporting
peace in the Middle East, security questions related to the Gulf,"
said White House spokesman Mike McCurry.
</P>
<P>
"They will talk about some of the efforts that we make together
to assure that the Gulf continues to be a reliable source of
energy resources for the world," he added
</P>
<P>
Prince Abdullah arrived in Washington Wednesday for a one-week
visit that is part of a world tour that includes stops in Britain
and France.
</P>
<P>
Clinton has rolled out the red carpet for Abdullah, sending
Vice President Al Gore to greet him on his arrival Wednesday and
hosting a working lunch for him at the White House Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Saudi Arabia, the world's largest oil producer, is a key ally
of the United States, which has a significant military presence in
the country.
</P>
<P>
Prince Abdullah's visit includes meetings with Gore and Deputy
U.S. Defense Secretary John Hamre Thursday as well as a session
next week with Federal Bureau of Investigation (FBI) director
Louis Freeh.
</P>
<P>
Abdullah is also expected to meet Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright and Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin. 
</P>
