<HEADLINE> IDB Finances Nicaragua to Modernize Banking System </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 24 (Xinhua) -- The Inter-American
Development Bank (IDB) Thursday announced the approval of 96
million U.S. dollars in financing to back the modernization of
Nicaragua's financial system and construction of a power plant.
</P>
<P>
Concessional financing of nearly 66 million dollars will
support a program that embodies a medium-term vision for the
financial system based on the principles of competitive and
efficient markets. Direct government intervention in the delivery
of financial services and the accompanying distortions it causes
will cease.
</P>
<P>
The IDB financing, from the Fund for Special Operations,
consists of a 65 million dollar sector loan and a 765,000 dollar
loan for technical cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Besides, a total of 30 million dollars in financing will
support the construction and operation of the country's first
private power plant since the country adopted a new law for the
electricity sector in 1997. The 50.9 megawatt diesel plant, to be
located 20 kilometers east of Managua, will help meet the
country's energy needs that are resulting from economic growth.
</P>
<P>
The financing consists of a 10.75 million dollar loan from
ordinary capital and 19.5 million dollars in financing to be
contributed by commercial banks under subscription of
participation agreements with the IDB. 
</P>
</TEXT>
