<HEADLINE> Israel Opposes Unilateral Declaration of Palestinian State </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 24 (Xinhua) -- The unilateral
declaration of a Palestinian state would cause the collapse of the
Middle East peace process, Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu said here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu was responding to the repeated statement by
Palestinian leaders that they would proclaim an independent state
if a final peace agreement with Israel was not concluded by next
May.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the 53rd Session of the General Assembly, Netanyahu
said the Oslo accords were not about meeting deadlines.
</P>
<P>
"An arbitrary, unilateral declaration of a Palestinian state,
in disregard of this purpose, would constitute a fundamental
violation of the Oslo accords. It would cause the complete
collapse of the process," the prime minister said.
</P>
<P>
"I strongly urge the Palestinian Authority not to take this
course. Such actions will inevitably prompt unilateral response on
our part," Netanyahu said.
</P>
<P>
"And this development will not be good for the Palestinians,
not good for Israel, not good for peace," he said.
</P>
<P>
"We must continue to negotiate, earnestly, continuously and
tirelessly, until a final peace agreement is reached. No other way
will do," he added.
</P>
<P>
Israel and the Palestinians have been at odds over a U.S.
initiative under which Israel would hand over an additional 13
percent of the West Bank in exchange for Palestinian security
measures of fighting terrorism. 
</P>
</TEXT>
