<HEADLINE> India to Sign CTBT Within Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 24 (Xinhua) -- India was prepared to
sign the Comprehensive Nuclear-Test-Ban-Treaty (CTBT) within one
year, Indian Prime Minister Atal Behari Vajpayee said here on
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the 53rd Session of the General Assembly of the
United Nations, Vajpayee said "We are prepared to bring these
discussions to a successful conclusion, so that the entry into
force of CTBT is not delayed beyond September 1999."
</P>
<P>
"India, having harmonized its national imperatives and security
obligations and desirous of continuing to cooperate with the
international community, is now engaged in discussions with key
interlocutors on a range of issues, including CTBT," the Prime
Minister said.
</P>
<P>
Vajpayee said India was already observed CTBT's basic
obligation since it announced a voluntary moratorium after
carrying out five underground tests in May.
</P>
<P>
The Prime Minister said his country expected other countries
would also adhere to the treaty unconditionally.  
</P>
