<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IFC Redoubles Commitments to Asian Countries in FY 1998 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 24 (Xinhua) -- The International Finance
Corporation (IFC) redoubled its commitments in Asian countries with
new investment and made more investments than ever in more
frontier economies around the world in 1998 fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
In its 1998 Annual Report released here Thursday, IFC said that
in the 1998 fiscal year, which ended on June 30, IFC committed to
investment in 226 projects, 23 more than the year before, with a
total commitment of 5.1 billion U.S. dollars. The commitment
consists of 2.7 billion dollars for its own account and 2.4
billion dollars for the account of participant banks. The IFC
signed investment in 73 countries and regions, up from 60 in 1997.
</P>
<P>
In order to help those hardest hit countries in the Asian
financial and economic crisis, IFC made new investments in Asia,
including four projects in South Korea, where it had not invested
in a decade, and two in Malaysia, where the Corporation re-entered
after an absence of seven years.
</P>
<P>
A total of 51 projects involving 1.1 billion dollars of
financing was approved and 768 million dollars was actually
committed to 30 projects in East Asia and the Pacific in the past
year.
</P>
<P>
To finance its lending program in developing countries, IFC
borrowed 4.1 billion dollars in 1998 fiscal year, almost entirely
in the international capital markets. IFC issued securities in 13
different currencies, including the Russian ruble, Estonian kroon,
and Israeli shekel.
</P>
<P>
IFC, founded in 1956 as the lending arm of the World Bank Group
for private sectors in developing countries, has 174 member
countries, including two new members added in the 1998 fiscal
year: Palau and Chad. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
