<HEADLINE> U.S. House Panel Announces Schedule for Impeachment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 24 (Xinhua) -- The Judiciary Committee of
the U.S. House of Representatives announced on Thursday it will
vote on October 5 or 6 whether to launch a formal impeachment
inquiry into charges against President Bill Clinton.
</P>
<P>
Chairman Henry Hyde, a Republican, said if the committee
approved the inquiry, the full House would vote on the measure,
probably on October 8 or 9.
</P>
<P>
"Like all Americans I want to bring this matter to closure as
soon as possible," Hyde said at a press conference. "The timetable
I've proposed today is the most expeditious schedule we can
follow. I urge everyone to be patient, allow our system of law to
work."
</P>
<P>
In a White House ceremony trumpeting the decline in the
nation's poverty rate, Clinton urged Congress to end political
wrangling and move ahead with other urgent business that Americans
were interested in.
</P>
<P>
But Congressional Republicans had made clear they would keep
impeachment before the public in the less than six weeks left
before the November election despite Democrats' calls to speed up
the process.
</P>
<P>
Hyde said at the end of next week the committee would be
briefed by its staff on the 65,000 pages of evidence handed over
by independent counsel Kenneth Starr but not yet released to the
public. The committee would meet in open session the following
week for the vote on whether to continue.
</P>
<P>
Among the items to be considered for the next round of public
release are the depositions of Clinton friend Vernon Jordan,
Clinton secretary Betty Currie, and Secret Service officers, a
transcript of the tapes of Lewinsky made by her former friend
Linda Tripp and the tapes themselves.
</P>
<P>
News reports quoted committee sources as saying that a battle
was still possible over release of the Tripp tapes, which contain
more sexual details but also material the Democrats think could
help the president.
</P>
<P>
"It's unacceptable to pretend to be conducting a bipartisan
investigation and then vote not to release the tapes," said
Representative Marty Meehan, a Democrat. "In the tapes, when you
can listen to them, you can get a better sense of the credibility
or lack of credibility."
</P>
<P>
Meehan also said he would like Starr himself to be called
before committee to answer questions.
</P>
<P>
At the White House, Clinton called for "progress over
partisanship... people over politics."
</P>
<P>
Asked if there was a way out of the scandal, Clinton said, "The
only way out is for people in Washington to do what the folks in
America want them to do, which is to take care of their concerns,
their children and their future. That's what I mean to do, and I'm
going to do my best." 
</P>
</TEXT>
