<HEADLINE> Mozambique Supports Military Intervention in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, September 24 (Xinhua) -- Mozambican President Joaquim
Chissano said here Thursday that the decision of the Southern
African Development Community (SADC) to send troops to Lesotho
was aimed at restoring peace in the country.
</P>
<P>
Chissano told reporters at the State House that there was no
alternative. He denied the claim that Mozambique's stance on
Lesotho issue goes against that on the Congo crisis.
</P>
<P>
"We have made the decision as a step to bring all parties
involved in the conflict to dialog," the Mozambican president
said, adding that "Lesotho has been paralyzed as a result of
violence, with government organs and other institutions of public
services all out of operation."
</P>
<P>
As the vice-chairman of the SADC, Chissano stressed that the
decision of sending troops to Lesotho had been unanimously agreed
by South Africa, Mozambique, Zimbabwe and Botswana.
</P>
<P>
However, he added that "we will continue to make efforts so as
to solve the (Lesotho) problem through dialog."
</P>
<P>
The Mozambican president noted that his country did not sent
troops to Lesotho because it doesn't afford to.
</P>
<P>
He further explained that "we believed that something could be
done ahead of military intervention" in the case of the
Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC).
</P>
<P>
The president pointed out that the decision on the DRC crisis
had been made by individual SADC states. Some countries,
especially those neighboring the DRC, regarded the crisis in the
country as explosive, said Chissano, therefore they decided to
intervene.
</P>
<P>
The troops of South Africa and Botswana entered into Lesotho
on Monday and met resistance by the mutinous Lesotho soldiers
with casualt on both sides.
</P>
<P>
The Lesotho crisis began when the opposition parties did not
accept the results of the May general elections, saying that the
government should resign because of its alleged rigging in the
votes. 
</P>
</TEXT>
