<HEADLINE> Interior Minister Offers to Resign Over Refugee Death </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, September 25 (Xinhua) -- The Belgian interior
minister has offered to resign over the death of a Nigerian
refugee but the cabinet would not accept the resignation.
</P>
<P>
A cabinet meeting Friday persuaded Louis Tobback to retrieve
his resignation letter which he had sent to the prime minister's
office late Thursday, according to a written statement issued
after the cabinet meeting.
</P>
<P>
Tobback said in another statement that he had offered to resign
because of police errors in preparing the deportation of
20-year-old Semira Adamu who died Tuesday after being restrained
by gendarmes.
</P>
<P>
The Nigerian woman died of a brain haemorrhage while being
subdued by the gendarmes who had escorted her aboard a
Nigeria-bound flight.
</P>
<P>
The fact that the police officers escorting Adamu had used a
cushion to muffle her screams has become a key issue for
investigation.
</P>
<P>
One of the two police officers under investigation over Adamu's
death has been disciplined in a similar case previously, according
to police sources.
</P>
<P>
The Belgian government has decided to suspend the country's
repatriation of refugees for the time being.
</P>
<P>
If Tobback's resignation was accepted, it would be the second
time within six months for a cabinet member to resign over errors
committed by the police.
</P>
<P>
In April this year, Tobback's predecessor resigned after
alleged child rapist and killer Marc Dutroux escaped from a
pre-trial hearing. 
</P>
</TEXT>
