<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australia's Labor Takes Lead Over Coalition: Polls </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, September 25 (Xinhua) -- The Australian Labor Party
(ALP) has taken a potentially decisive lead over the coalition of
the Liberal and National parties, with Opposition Leader Kim
Beazley clearly out-campaigning Prime Minister John Howard, the
major polls this week showed.
</P>
<P>
As the election campaign enters its final week, the average of
the four polls over the past week showed support for ALP climbing
for the second week in a row to 42.1 percent.
</P>
<P>
Support for the coalition, meanwhile, fell for the first time
since the election was called on August 30, to 40.4 percent, a 1.7
point margin.
</P>
<P>
Labor is now ahead in three of the four polls - Newspoll, AC
Nielsen and Morgan, but trails badly in the Bulletin poll.
</P>
<P>
The fact the government's support fell in three of the polls
and was steady in the fourth indicates its campaign has run into
serious trouble.
</P>
<P>
After opening the election campaign two points behind the ALP,
the government received a significant surge in support in the
opening week to take an early lead.
</P>
<P>
But Labor, pegging back the government's lead in the second
week, has surged ahead over the past fortnight on the back of the
election debate between Howard and Beazley.
</P>
<P>
Although the polls clearly favor the ALP pulling off a
remarkable political comeback, returning Labor to power after only
one term in opposition, Beazley has said the mathematics were
against his party.
</P>
<P>
To win the October 3 election, the ALP must pick up an extra 27
seats, a task which will require a national swing of about four
percent.
</P>
<P>
Now the ALP has pinned its hopes on substantial gains in
Queensland and Victoria, as well as a few extra seats from
Tasmania. Beazley will venture into the National Party's heartland
in central Queensland.
</P>
<P>
Howard will campaign in Victoria where Labor has attracted
strong support.
</P>
<P>
So far as small parties are concerned, the One Nation Party is
the clear loser of the election campaign, with support steadily
sliding throughout the campaign. Pauline Hanson's support stood at
nine percent the week the election was called and has fallen every
week since to the present 6.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
The Australian Democrats have been one of the major
beneficiaries whose support has now climbed to 5.1 percent, up one
percent from the start of the campaign. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980925.0048 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hosts Maintain Domination at China Cup Gymnastics </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIANJIN, September 25 (Xinhua) -- Host China maintained its
invincible momentum in the individuals finals on the second and
final day of the China Cup International Gymnastics Tournament,
taking nine of the 10 golds up for grabs here on Friday.
</P>
<P>
The only gold slipping away from the Chinese hands was the
horizontal bar, where both of the Chinese athletes, all-round
champion Huang Xu and his teammate Lu Yufu, fell off the bar. The
title was taken by Japanese Isao Yoneda with a superb 9.750
routine.
</P>
<P>
Bulgarian Hr. Ivanov and another Japanese A. Kasamatsu coming
on second and third, respectively.
</P>
<P>
Otherwise, the home crowd was treated to spirited performances
from China's young waves of gymnasts, led by 15-year-old Ling Jie
from Hu Nan province, who stole the limelight by two impeccable
performances on beam and uneven bars, which each earned her a
meet-high 9.850 and a pair of golds.
</P>
<P>
Her world cup champion teammate Liu Xuan had to settle for the
bronze on uneven bars, tying French national champion Elvire Teza
on 9.725 but lower than the silver medalist in the team event
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Another dazzling Chinese gymnast was world cup champion Li
Xiaopeng, winner of both the vault and parallel bars with 9.650
and 9.800 points respectively, serving note he may be the next
undisputed master of China's men gymnastics.
</P>
<P>
Much-touted Lu Yufu salvaged his China Cup trip by snagging
the gold with a 9.625 routine on men's floor exercise after
muffing his chances in yesterday's all-round event.
</P>
<P>
Local hero Dong Zhen gave the 5000-strong crowd something to
cheer about by swing to the rings title with a 9.800. His
teammates Zhao Sheng and Huang Xu rounded out the top three for
China.
</P>
<P>
Zhao, Thursday's all-round silver medalist, took his medal
haul to four by garnering the pommel horse title, edging A.
Kasamatsu of Japan and V. Vezchev of Bulgaria.
</P>
<P>
The women's vault title also went to China. Olympian Kui
Yuanyuan vaulted on a solid landing to notch up a 9.537 and the
gold medal.
</P>
<P>
The women's floor seemed to be a close battle between Kui's
two teammates Huang Mandan and Rao Meizhen and the American girl
Elise Ray. Huang displayed a near-flawless 9.775 floor to take
the gold, beating Ray and all-round titlist Rao into second and
third on 9.750 and 9.600 respectively. 
</P>
</TEXT>
