<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine President Urges Strict Enforcement of </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, September 25 (Xinhua) -- Philippine President Joseph
Estrada said Friday that transport and maritime authorities under
his administration will strictly enforce safety rules to prevent
another sea disaster from happening.
</P>
<P>
Estrada told reporters that maritime authorities have
recommended stricter safety procedure and measures for seafaring
vessels after the sinking of a passenger ferry last Friday.
</P>
<P>
Estrada said he will not risk another mishap by lifting with
haste the preventive suspension imposed on Sulpicio Lines whose
inter-island ferry M/V Princess of the Orient sank off at the
mouth of Manila Bay last Friday.
</P>
<P>
The president also stressed that he does not want the
government to get blamed either for allowing un-seaworthy ships to
ply maritime routes, or for obstructing business by grounding
passenger ships.
</P>
<P>
Maritime authorities have suspended operations of Sulpicio
Lines pending an investigation into the mishap which left more
than 100 people dead.
</P>
<P>
The sea accident was the third involving this ferry operator
since 1987, when more than 4,000 passengers died after its ship
M/V Dona Paz collided with an oil tanker in one of the world's
worst maritime disasters. Ten months later, another Sulpicio-owned
vessel M/V Marilyn sank, killing more than 200 people. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
