<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ethiopia Earns More from Tea Export </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, September 25 (Xinhua) -- Ethiopia earned 573,365
U.S. Dollars from tea export in 1997/98 financial year ending on
July 7, 1998, more than doubled that in the previous year,
according to an announcement made by the Ethiopian Coffee and Tea
Development Authority.
</P>
<P>
A local report Friday quoted the authority as saying that the
nation exported 226 tons of tea in 1997/98, compared with 115
tons in 1996/97. Out of the total 1997/98 export, 183 tons were
exported to Djibouti, 23 tons to Pakistan and 20 tons to Canada.
</P>
<P>
Tea was first grown in Ethiopia some 70 years ago but
commercial farming did not start until the early 1980s. In
1997/98 the country sold a total of 1,531 tons of tea, in which,
226 tons was exported abroad and the balance went to the local
market.
</P>
<P>
Ethiopia has planned to put six million hectares of land in
western Ethiopia for tea farm to expand production, and also to
end near-total dependence on coffee for hard currency earnings.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
