<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-25 15:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 3 Lebanese Wounded in South Lebanon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, September 25 (Xinhua) -- Three Lebanese, including a
child and two Israeli-allied South Lebanon Army (SLA) militiamen,
were wounded in separate military conflicts in south Lebanon on
Friday, the Orient radio reported.
</P>
<P>
Ten-year-old Hussein Harb was wounded by Israeli shelling on
Iqlim Toufah area, a stronghold of the Iranian-backed Hezbollah,
or Party of God, which lies just north of the Israeli occupied
border strip in south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Hezbollah is spearheading a guerrilla war to oust more than
1,000 Israeli troops and their allied SLA militia from south
Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Israel set up a self-declared security zone in south Lebanon in
1985 with the claimed aim to protect its north from cross-border
attacks by Lebanese guerrillas.
</P>
<P>
Also in the day, the Amal movement, Lebanon's another
anti-Israeli Muslim group led by House Speaker Nabih Berri, said
that one of its units launched a machine-gun and grenade attack on
a SLA post at Suwidai village in Iqlim Toufah, killing or wounding
its members.
</P>
<P>
The SLA's official radio Voice of the South later confirmed
the casualties, saying two of its soldiers were wounded during
the clash.
</P>
<P>
The Amal's attack has brought to 38 the number of SLA
militiamen wounded in south Lebanon so far this year, in addition
to 27 killed.
</P>
<P>
Heavy losses the Israeli forces and the SLA have suffered
during the past years forced them into rethinking the wisdom of
keeping presence in south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
In April this year, Israel offered to withdraw from south
Lebanon provided that Lebanese government agreed on a negotiated
security guarantee for Israeli north.
</P>
<P>
A week ago, the SLA made a similar offer, saying it is ready to
withdraw from its controlled Jezzine, a predominantly Christian
town north of the occupied zone.
</P>
<P>
But it conditioned the withdrawal on that Lebanese government
troops agree to take over the vacated area to prevent Muslim
guerrillas from attacking them from there.
</P>
<P>
Beirut rejected both the offers, asking Israel to withdraw from
occupied Lebanese lands without any preconditions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
