<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian Dollar Rallies Strongly </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, September 25 (Xinhua) -- The Australian dollar
rallied strongly Friday, finishing the session more than half a
U.S. cent higher.
</P>
<P>
The Arab Bank foreign exchange dealer, Scott Young, said the
local currency had been consistently bid on the day.
</P>
<P>
"It ran into some sellers around 58.55 U.S. cents first up and
backed off a little," he said.
</P>
<P>
But the bids were still there for the Australian dollar and it
traded to a high of 58.83 U.S. cents.
</P>
<P>
The Australian dollar closed at 58.73 U.S. cents from 58.15
here Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
He said the possibility of more downside for the U.S. dollar
was also a boost for the local currency.
</P>
<P>
A rate cut in the U.S. would also lend a bid undertone to
commodities which would help the Australian dollar.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. dollar was at 135.46 Japanese yen from 136.58 and
1.6747 German marks from 1.6833 Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The fact that weakness in the U.S. dollar against European
currencies could not be translated as strongly to the U.S.
dollar/Japanese yen exchange rate was holding back moves in the
Australian dollar.
</P>
<P>
"Because the yen is not keeping pace, Aussie is lagging a
little bit behind," Young said
</P>
<P>
On the cross-rates, the local currency was buying 79.52
Japanese yen from 79.43 and 0.9826 German marks from 0.9786.
</P>
</TEXT>
