<HEADLINE> Angola, Namibia Sign Defense Cooperation Treaty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, September 25 (Xinhua) -- Angola and Namibia Thursday
signed a treaty on security and defense cooperation at the end of
a joint meeting between defense officials of the two south
African countries, which was held in Namibia's capital, Windhoek.
</P>
<P>
The treaty would be effective after the approval of respective
governments, said Roberto Leal Monteiro, Vice Minister of Defense
and head of the Angola delegation to the fifth meeting of the
Joint Committee of the two countries, according to reports
reaching here Friday.
</P>
<P>
Monteiro said that experts at the meeting mapped out a
fundamental document on strengthening the security and defense
cooperation between the two neighboring countries.
</P>
<P>
The treaty covers the enhanced management of the border line
security, the promotion of bilateral trade, the development of
tourism, the joint effort on cracking down cross-border crimes
like automobile and livestock theft. 
</P>
</TEXT>
