<DOCNO> XIE19980925.0065 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Opinion Survey to Be Conducted on HK's New Airport </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, September 25 (Xinhua) -- Hu Fa-kuang, chairman of
Hong Kong's Airport Consultative Committee (ACC), said Friday
that the ACC is commissioning an opinion survey on the new Hong
Kong International Airport at Chek Lap Kok.
</P>
<P>
During a visit to the airport with 13 other members of the ACC,
Hu said that this survey, to be carried out next month, aims at
seeking the views of four key groups of people, including arriving
and departing passengers, clients of air cargo companies and
management staff of airlines and air cargo companies, airport
users other than passengers, and members of the general public.
</P>
<P>
"We hope the views canvassed will represent a wide
cross-section of airport users as well as those who have not been
to the airport," Hu said.
</P>
<P>
"The results will reflect the level of services provided at the
airport and also give us an idea on areas where further
improvements are necessary," he added.
</P>
<P>
The survey will be conducted by the Social Sciences Research
Center of the University of Hong Kong in October and results are
expected in December, he said.
</P>
<P>
During the three-hour visit, K K Kwok, director of the New
Airport Projects Co-ordination Office, told the ACC members that
the brand new airport is functioning smoothly as a result of the
dedicated work of the many thousands of people working there.
</P>
<P>
The ACC party observed operations in the arrival and departure
halls and in the restricted areas as well as the baggage reclaim
hall. They also inspected operations at the Hong Kong Air Cargo
Terminals.
</P>
<P>
Kwok said arriving passengers wait no longer than 15 minutes at
immigration counters and are able to reclaim their baggage in
about 10 minutes on average.
</P>
<P>
At the end of the visit, Hu said while he was pleased with what
he had seen, efforts should be made to ascertain the views of
airport users so that further improvements could be made. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980925.0066 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roast Beijing Duck Originated in Nanjing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Hu Changlin, the reputed leading chef in south China, said that
roast duck, pig and fish have been Nanjing's delicacies since
ancient times.
</P>
<P>
Zhu Yuanzhang, the first emperor of Ming Dynasty (1368-1644
A.D.), established his capital in Nanjing, and shortly thereafter
roast duck was added to the imperial menu.
</P>
<P>
His son Zhu Li ascended to the throne and moved the capital and
indeed the secret of roast duck to Beijing. The sweet brown sauce,
green onions and thin pancakes characteristic of Shandong Province
were added to Beijing roast duck.
</P>
<P>
The delicacy soon spread from the emperor's palace and became a
famous dish in the Chinese capital.
</P>
<P>
Some people say the Beijing dish is somewhat salty, but roast
Beijing duck is nonetheless lighter and sweeter than the typical
Nanjing flavor. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980925.0067 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Curtain Falls on Pacific Rim Forum </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, September 25 (Xinhua) -- The annual meeting of the
Pacific Rim Forum closed today in Shanghai's Pudong New Area.
</P>
<P>
Over 400 well-known experts from 18 countries and regions
attended the meeting and exhibited growing concern about the
negative effects the financial crisis sweeping Southeast Asia will
have on the rest of the world.
</P>
<P>
The participants urged all nations effected by financial crisis
to reform and restructure their economies in order to improve
their capacity to resist financial instability.
</P>
<P>
However, they noted the financial crisis might provide some
nations with a rare opportunity healthy economic development once
they overcome the initial negative impacts.
</P>
<P>
The majority of participants from developing countries agreed
that the globalization of the world economy is inevitable, but
stressed that individual countries should select their approaches
in accordance with unique national conditions.
</P>
<P>
They called for a new world economic order based on equality
and justice, and emphasized that developed countries should
tolerate and understand the achievements developing countries are
making in terms of globalization.
</P>
<P>
Dan Huber, an manager with U.S-based Cargill, expressed
amazement at changes which have taken place in Shanghai. He said
the municipality mirrors the healthy development of the Chinese
economy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
