<HEADLINE> Yeltsin Appoints Ten New Government Ministers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, September 25 (Xinhua) -- Russian President Boris
Yeltsin on Friday issued decrees to appoint a largest number of
new ministers to fill ministerial posts in the cabinet of Prime
Minister Yevgeny Primakov.
</P>
<P>
Despite the latest appointments, 10 vacancies in the cabinet
still remain unfilled.
</P>
<P>
The appointments, as reported by the Itar-Tass news agency,
were as follows:
</P>
<P>
Georgy Gabuniya as the Minister of Trade, Andrei Shapovalyants
as the Minister of Economics, Valery Kirpichnikov as the Minister
of Science and Technology, Ramazan Abdulatipov as the Minister of
National Policy, Sergei Frank as the Minister of Transport,
Sergei Generalov as the Minister of Fuel and Energy, Pavel
Krasheninnikov as the Minister of Justice, Boris Pastukhov as the
Minister for Affairs of the Commonwealth of Independent States,
Nikolai Aksyonenko as the Minister of Railways, and Mikhail
Zadornov as the Finance Minister.
</P>
<P>
On Thursday, after a prolonged consideration, Yeltsin made the
decision to appoint 49-year former ambassador to Greece Valentina
Matviyenko as the deputy prime minister in charge of social
affairs.
</P>
<P>
So far, all the six posts of deputy prime ministers, including
two first deputy premiers, in the new Cabinet have been occupied.
</P>
<P>
The appointment of the finance minister also took a long time
to make a decision as the post is very important to the government.
</P>
<P>
On Tuesday, a presidential decree declared the structure of
Russian federal executive power institutions includes 24
ministries, 13 state committees, two federal commissions, 17
federal services, three Russian agencies, two federal
inspectorates and four federal institutions of other types.
</P>
<P>
As of today, 14 out of the 24 ministers have been appointed.
The interior minister, the defense minister, the foreign minister
and the minister for civil defense, emergency situations and
management of natural disasters were appointed on September 11,
when Yevgeny Primakov was approved by the State Duma as the Prime
Minister. 
</P>
</TEXT>
