<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesian Attorney General Gets Draft Letters From </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, September 25 (Xinhua) -- Indonesian former president
Soeharto Friday submitted two draft letters needed by the Attorney
General's Office to pursue investigations on his alleged hidden
wealth.
</P>
<P>
Attorney General Andi M. Ghalib told reporters that the
submission of the draft letters marks the start of the preliminary
investigations into the wealth the former president has allegedly
amassed during his 32 years in power.
</P>
<P>
President B.J. Habibie last week approved the formation of a
team, led by Ghalib and helped by the police and the Development
and Finance Comptroller, to question Soeharto in person.
</P>
<P>
Ghalib said the first draft letter constituted a special power
of attorney that would enable the Attorney General to receive
money from the alleged bank accounts under Soeharto's name, to be
later transferred to the government.
</P>
<P>
The second draft letter allows foreign banks to provide the
Attorney General's Office with information on the alleged bank
accounts under Soeharto's name.
</P>
<P>
Soeharto, who stepped down amid mounting public pressure on May
21, has repeatedly said that he had no money, stocks or valuable
papers abroad and had never held any offshore bank accounts.
</P>
<P>
He also challenged anyone with corroborating evidence to report
the banks to the Attorney General's Office, and said he would
authorize that particular financial institution to release details
of the accounts.
</P>
<P>
Ghalib told reporters that he will soon form two teams, the
first to be in charge of tracing alleged bank accounts under
Soeharto's name and the second to be in charge of tracing
Soeharto's wealth.
</P>
<P>
He called on the people to stay calm and patient as the
investigations are still in their early stage.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, House of Representatives/People's Consultative
Assembly Speaker Harmoko told reporters Friday that he believed
the government is already seriously investigating Soeharto's
wealth through the Attorney General's Office.
</P>
<P>
"But if the government later proves not to be, the House will
use its 'right to query' to question the government about the
effort," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
