<HEADLINE> More Ethiopians Doing Business With Djibouti </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, September 25 (Xinhua) -- More Ethiopians have
been doing business with their counterparts in Djibouti since
Ethiopian-Eritrean border dispute erupted last May, which cut off
Ethiopia's trade outlet in Eritrea.
</P>
<P>
A total of 1,730 small border area traders have been licensed
following the implementation of the Ethiopian-Djibouti border
trade agreement in May of this year, the Ethiopian Herald Friday
quoted a statement issued by the Dire Dawa foreign trade office
as saying.
</P>
<P>
Dire Dawa, second largest city in Ethiopia, is located at the
middle of 781-km Addis Ababa-Djibouti railway line. After the
border dispute between Ethiopia and Eritrea erupted last May,
Ethiopia had diverted its trade outlet from Assab port of Eritrea
to port of Djibouti.
</P>
<P>
The statement said the number of border traders has shown a
dramatic increase because the foreign trade office has devised a
plan to replace illegal traders by lawfully operating ones.
</P>
<P>
Accordik7to the agreement between the governments of Ethiopia
and Djibouti, these small traders may import and export goods
worth no more than 285 US Dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
