<HEADLINE> Australian Stocks End Lower on Bearish U.S. Markets </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, September 25 (Xinhua) -- The Australian sharemarket
finished sharply lower Friday, weighed down by bearish sentiment
in the United States, losses in key Asian markets and local
profit-taking.
</P>
<P>
Traders said news of the bailout of Long-Term Capital
Management LP in the United States also unsettled investors.
</P>
<P>
The all ordinaries index closed 51.5 points lower at 2,563.4,
following the lead of Wall Street overnight and Asian markets
Friday.
</P>
<P>
News in America that federal banking authorities helped arrange
a 3.5 billion U.S. dollars bailout of the hedge fund, Long Term
Capital Management, also was unsettling the market. Some of the
money was borrowed from commercial banks and investment houses.
</P>
<P>
Sixteen of the world's largest banks and brokerage firms were
believed to have put up money to bailout the fund, which had more
than 90 billion U.S. dollars invested in markets around the world,
but especially bonds.
</P>
<P>
Locally, the all industrials index finished down 100.3 points
at 4,492.8, while the all resources index fell just 10.4 points at
1,009.0.
</P>
<P>
Traders noticed a strong shift out of the industrial sector in
particular the banks, into resource stocks -- particularly gold
stocks -- with the gold index up more than five percent.
</P>
<P>
The gold index finished the day up 55 points at 1,111.5 on the
back of the fortunes of the precious metal overnight. In Sydney
gold closed at 294.25 U.S. dollars an ounce up from 291.35.
</P>
<P>
Among other resource stocks, BHP fell 51.1 cents, or 3.99
percent, Rio Tinto defied the downward trend to be 21.5 cents
firmer, WMC fell two cents, on turnover of 9.05 million, Comalco
slipped 10, North gave up 11.2 cents.
</P>
<P>
Banking stocks shed ground over concerns about the hedge fund
in the U.S. reporting huge losses Thursday night and the
implications that others might be joining it as well.
</P>
<P>
The banking index ended 135.9 points, or 2.40 percent weaker at
5,521.3 points.
</P>
<P>
Among the banks, National Australia Bank was off 54.2 cents,
CBA had shed 53, ANZ lost 14.6 and Westpac slipped 29.
</P>
<P>
Among industrial stocks, Telstra topped volume with 19.92
million installment receipts traded. Media heavyweight News Corp
fell 47 cents, and its preferred shares slipped 57.5.
</P>
<P>
National turnover climbed to 364.53 million shares valued at
1.45 billion Australian dollars (852.6 million U.S. dollars).
Falls outpaced rises by 581 to 409, with 308 stocks steady.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
