<DOCNO> XIE19980925.0082 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine President Firm Against Govt Takeover of PAL </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, September 25 (Xinhua) -- Philippine President Joseph
Estrada remained firm Friday on his decision against any
government takeover of Philippine Airlines (PAL), saying such a
move will further bleed anemic state coffers.
</P>
<P>
Estrada said that aside from having to deal with PAL's
creditors and the airline's debts amounting to over 90 billion
pesos (2.1 billion U.S. dollars), the government also stands to
lose more than 45 to 50 million pesos a day should it take over
the airline's operations.
</P>
<P>
Estrada said he was fully aware that under the law and PAL's
Charter, the government can take over the airline to protect the
public interest.
</P>
<P>
PAL ceased operations at midnight Wednesday due to its
worsening financial situation and protracted labor dispute.
</P>
<P>
Estrada said a government takeover would be futile because some
45 to 50 million pesos in public finds will be spent daily on an
unsafe investment and without even resolving the long-standing
dispute between the airline's labor unions and management.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Estrada denied reports that he had "coddled" PAL
chairman Lucio Tan, saying he even persuaded the businessman to
keep the airline operating for at least one month despite huge
losses. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
