<DOCNO> XIE19980925.0083 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Water Levels of Yangtze R. Below Warning Line at All Points </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 25 (Xinhua) -- Water levels at all
monitoring stations along the Yangtze River have dropped below
warning marks, according to the State Flood Control and Drought
Relief Headquarters.
</P>
<P>
This year's 53rd flood status report issued by the headquarters
points to current water levels as a mark of the historic victory
over the extended period of devastating summer floods which
affected China's longest river.
</P>
<P>
Record water levels were recored at all points along the main
channel stream of the Yangtze River throughout the flood season.
</P>
<P>
For example, flood waters surpassed warning marks for 57 days
and hit record highs over 12 days at Shashi, central China's Hubei
Province. Jiujiang, east China's Jiangxi Province, recorded flood
water above warning marks for 94 days and record highs for 40 days.
</P>
<P>
Water levels in flood-ravaged areas along the Nenjiang and
Songhua rivers in northeastern provinces continue to recede,
according to the report.
</P>
<P>
However, water levels at monitoring stations in in Dalai,
Jilin Province, and Tonghe and Fujin in Heilongjiang Province
continue to hover at warning marks.
</P>
<P>
The year's record flooding, the worst since 1954, killed 3,004
people and adversely affected over 240 million people. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
