<DOCNO> XIE19980925.0095 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Employment Situation Improving </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 25 (Xinhua) -- The State Statistics Bureau
says that China's reform has created more job opportunities and
that, by 1997, there were approximately 700 million people at
work, 214.85 million more than in 1978.
</P>
<P>
Rapid growth in the private sector has helped this a great
deal, it reports.
</P>
<P>
Reforms have helped the employment structure, and the number of
employees in the service sector in 1997 was 3.8 times that of
1978, an average annual growth rate of 7.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
The SSB says that there was a rise in the number of female
employees during the period. In 1997, there were 323.64 million,
accounting for 46.5 percent of the working population.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, more educated people have joined the labor force
since 1978. There were 24.36 million college graduates at work in
1997, 5.4 times the 1982 figure, according to SSB.
</P>
<P>
The SSB says that China's labor market system has played a
major role in job searches as more job placement centers are
formed.
</P>
<P>
However, there are still the problems of laid-off workers and
the social security system, the bureau says, and a unified
comprehensive new social security system is urgently needed.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
