<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ITU Meeting In Beijing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 25 (Xinhua) -- Today was the last day of the
Study Group 7 of the International Telecommunications Union's
Telecommunications Standardization Bureau (ITU-T) meeting.
</P>
<P>
It was one of the most successful, according to ITU-T director
Theodor Irmer, who arrived in Beijing on Friday. He said that
these meetings are usually held at ITU headquarters in Geneva and
that this is the first time for the world's most authoritative
telecommunications organization to hold a decision-making meeting
in China.
</P>
<P>
ITU has 188 members around the world. The Study Group 7 of
ITU-T is in charge of putting forward universal technological
standards for data network and communications.
</P>
<P>
Herb Bertine, chairman of Study Group seven, said that during
the two-week meeting, about 30 technological recommendations were
approved and another 30 were discussed and prepared for approval
at the next meeting in June, 1999.
</P>
<P>
More than 90 governmental and telecommunications company
representatives attended the meeting. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980925.0101 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lesotho Cabinet Refuses to Talk to Opposition </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, September 25 (Xinhua) -- The Lesotho government
headed by Prime Minister Pakalitha Mosisili Friday rejected
proposed talks with opposition parties on resolving the crisis in
the country.
</P>
<P>
The monarch of the mountain country King Letsie III has been
reportedly attempting to bring the government and opposition to
the negotiating table, but the country's Foreign Minister Tom
Thabane rejected the king's proposal.
</P>
<P>
"How can we talk to political leaders who appear to have
encouraged their supporters to commit crime and sow anarchy
throughout the country," Thabane was quoted as saying by the
South African Press Association.
</P>
<P>
Thabane said those responsible for the mayhem, arson and
looting of shops in the capital of Maseru and other parts of the
country in the past three days should face the "strong arm of the
law".
</P>
<P>
It was reported that Lesotho's opposition parties had accepted
the king's invitation for round-table talks to resolve the
political crisis stemming from claims that the May 23 general
election was rigged in favor of the LDC.
</P>
<P>
Vincent Malebo, spokesman for the opposition alliance, said
Friday: "We are ready for talks with the government, but only
under the leadership of the king. The ball is now in the hands
of the government."
</P>
<P>
There were unconfirmed reports that King Letsie III had been
on the side of opposition parties. His palace was once used as
headquarters for opposition party supporters.
</P>
<P>
The opposition believed that talks could help resolve the
crisis in the country caused by "forces of aggression", said
Malebo, apparently referring to the military intervention early
this week by South Africa and Botswana at the request of the
Mosisili government.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwe and Mozambique have also expressed full support for
the military intervention in favor of the Lesotho government.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
