<HEADLINE> Duo Expelled from Tour of Spain for Failing Blood Test </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MADRID, September 25 (Xinhua) -- Daniel Clavero and Juan
Carlos Dominguez of the Vitalicio Seguros team, both failed the
official blood test, were thrown out of the Tour of Spain which
reached Alto De Navacerrada on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Calveros was lying seventh overall before Friday's 20th stage.
</P>
<P>
The two Spaniards were expelled after Union Cycliste
Internationale testers had made their early-morning call at five
team hotels in Segovia.
</P>
<P>
The tests were introduced last January to protect "the health,
safety, and welfare" of racers.
</P>
<P>
Anyone who had a blood concentration, known as the haematocrit
level, exceeding 50 percent is considered unfit to race.
</P>
<P>
Alex Zuelle, winner of the last two Tours, was cleared after
tests on Friday. He and some of his Festina team mates face
suspensions because of alleged use of erythropoietin, which
artifically enhances the oxygen carrying capacity of the blood.
</P>
<P>
Other teams tested included those of race leader Abraham Olano
and his chief rivals, Frenchman Laurent Jalabert and Spain's
Fernando Escartin. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
