<DOCNO> XIE19980925.0107 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Words Enter Chinese Vocabulary (1) by Yu Zheng and Hao Jinghua </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 25 (Xinhua) -- When U.S. President Richard
Nixon strolled on the Great Wall in 1972, the noise from his
pocket amazed almost all the Chinese security personnel, but more
than two decades later, anybody on the streets of Beijing knows
what a beeper is.
</P>
<P>
The beeper was still an alien in the world's most populous
country when it opened its doors to the outside world in late
1978. And, people knew little about some new words like the
"market economy", "stock market speculation", "karaoke", "cool",
"multimedia", "web surfing", and the "mobile phone".
</P>
<P>
But, economic reforms and science and technology are making
these everyday words now and people can easily find them in the
media.
</P>
<P>
According to the State Language Commission, China's most
authoritative voice on standardized usage, the country has
published more than 30 dictionaries of new words in the last
decade.
</P>
<P>
More fresh words and phrases appearing in various areas in the
country keep those lexicographers busy.
</P>
<P>
The reforms and opening up have eased the social situation in
China, says Dong Kun, a research fellow at the Chinese Academy of
Social Sciences' Institute of Linguistics, and many new words have
appeared and interesting phrases developed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980925.0108 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Words (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
As 'market economy' becomes a pet phrase of state leaders,
common people use the 'credit card', and "second occupation"
(meaning moonlighting) or "Xiahai" (jumping into the sea of
commerce), meaning quitting one's life-long job to do business on
one's own.
</P>
<P>
China's bullish market in the stock exchange brought many new
words about stocks, words like "Gumin" and "Guping", meaning
shareholders and comments on the stock market respectively.
</P>
<P>
With the freedoms and more open-minded society, Chinese are
accepting the challenges they are meeting in daily lives, and
"Xiagang" and "Zaijiuye", meaning unemployment and re-employment,
and "Zhongdiangong", or piece workers, have come into existence.
</P>
<P>
This shows the changes and adjustments they've made in their
minds, Dong says.
</P>
<P>
Hundreds of new phrases have appeared annually in recent years,
says Yu Genyuan, a research fellow at the State Language
Commission's Institute of Applied Linguistics. More than 7,000 new
words have become common since 1978, he says.
</P>
<P>
The tidal wave of facts and new ideas and concepts resulted in
new expressions during the social transformation, Yu explains. He
has led the state's only research group of study of new words and
their usage.
</P>
<P>
China has seen a lot of new words come and go over the
years. During the Northern and Southern Dynasties (420-589), there
were many borrowings in the northern and southern parts of the
country. The spread of Buddhism during the Tang Dynasty
(618-907) also introduced many words to China.
</P>
<P>
After the democratic movement of May 4, 1919, foreign words
from politics and the sciences used by the intelligentsia spread
across the country.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980925.0109 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Words (3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
In contrast to the extreme political language of the new
People's Republic of China in 1949 and the difficulties during the
Cultural Revolution (1966-1976), economic words are becoming more
active in modern times.
</P>
<P>
"The rigid, frozen, and combative linguistic style has been
changed into soft, smooth, polite and humane forms in many cases,"
Dong says.
</P>
<P>
As Chinese become familiar with the Internet and VCDs these
days, they can look back at the 1970s and the most luxurious items
that everyone wanted, the watch, bicycle and sewing machine.
</P>
<P>
By the early 1980s, it had become color TV sets. Although a
great number of words used at that time did not survive, some are
still in use, like "Tequ", or 'special economic zone', "Lixiu",
meaning veteran revolutionaries who have retired from
government posts, or "Xiangzhen Qiye", or township-run
enterprises.
</P>
<P>
Along with the national development, some new words and phrases
can be expected to last for a period of time, phrases
like 'invigorating China through science and education', 'economic
soft landing', 'high-tech', 'poverty relief', 'intellectual
property rights', and of course 'one country, two systems'.
</P>
<P>
"The changes in the style of the Chinese language show the
society becoming more relaxed and free, and the people becoming
humorous rather than poker-faced," says Zhou Hongbo, associate
research fellow at Commercial Press's dictionary editing section.
</P>
<P>
One British linguist said that one should never use a
dictionary that is more than ten years old, but in today's China,
some dictionaries are out of date a lot sooner than that.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980925.0110 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
