<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hope Dashed for Early Ending of Fuel Scarcity in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, September 25 (Xinhua) -- Hope of an early ending of
lingering fuel scarcity in Nigeria has been dashed following the
announcement that repair work on a major refinery in Kaduna would
take 14 more months.
</P>
<P>
Alhaji Dalhatu Bayero, the managing director of the Nigerian
National Petroleum Corporation (NNPC), who was accompanying
Nigerian leader Abdulsalam Abubakar on his visit to the United
Nations, made the disclosure Thursday in New York.
</P>
<P>
According to Bayero, the Turn-Around Maintenance (TAM) of the
Kaduna Refinery in north Nigeria would be postponed for 14 months
because of the need to replace damaged boilers and turbines.
</P>
<P>
The maintenance of the Kaduna refinery, being handled by the
French oil company Total at a cost of 217 million U.S. Dollars,
was expected to have been finished two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
It was reportedly earlier that the maintenance could not be
finished on time because of serious damages to key equipment
during ocean transportation.
</P>
<P>
Total has been accused of being technically unfit to handle
the job, but the French firm insisted that it undertake the job
as agreed and would finish the TAM by year end.
</P>
<P>
The NNPC official said Nigeria would take remedial measures to
mitigate the effect of the delay.
</P>
<P>
The measures include taking crude meant for the Kaduna plant
to overseas refineries for processing and importing 40 batches of
fuel cargoes, totaling 146.6 million liters for the fourth
quarter of this year.
</P>
<P>
Nigeria, a major world oil producer with a daily production of
over two million barrels, has been suffering from lingering fuel
scarcity in the past few years, due to ailing refineries.
</P>
<P>
The former government of late General Sani Abacha has been
accused of deliberately letting down the refineries so as to
profit from massive fuel importation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
