<HEADLINE> Hong Kong Restaurant Receipts Decline in Second Quarter </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, September 25 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong's restaurant
receipts and purchases continued to decline in the second quarter
of 1998, the government reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
The total restaurant receipts decreased by four percent in the
second quarter on a year-on-year base to 13.8 billion HK dollars
(1.8 billion U.S. dollars), while the total purchases made by
restaurants fell by seven percent to 4.8 billion HK dollars (62
million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
The Census and Statistics Department said that the receipts
shrank by seven percent in volume after discounting the effect of
inflation.
</P>
<P>
Chinese restaurants were hit hardest, with total revenues
slumping by ten percent in value and 12 percent in volume. Bars
also suffered from slack business, with receipts down 0.2 percent
in value and seven percent in volume.
</P>
<P>
Non-Chinese restaurants saw their total receipts up four
percent in value and roughly unchanged in volume.
</P>
<P>
Fast food shops, miscellaneous eating and drinking stores buck
the trend to record a rise of five to six percent in the value of
total receipts, and an increase of two to three percent in volume.
</P>
<P>
The half-year total restaurant receipts dropped by four percent
in value and eight percent in volume compared with the same period
of 1997. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980925.0120 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> France to Assist Nigeria in French Language </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, September 25 (Xinhua) -- The French government has
pledged to assist Nigeria in its efforts to make French its
second official language in the west African country.
</P>
<P>
Bruno Aguesse, Attache for Cultural, Scientific and Technical
Cooperation of the French Embassy to Nigeria, made the remarks
Thursday at a reception in honor of the winners of this year's
French Competitions organized by the Nigerian Association of
French Teachers.
</P>
<P>
He said that in cooperation with state ministry of education,
the French government had selected 90 secondary schools
throughout Nigeria for its pilot scheme to introduce French into
secondary schools, The Post Express reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
Under the scheme which is aimed at improving the teaching of
French, he noted, students in the selected secondary schools can
learn the language for six years.
</P>
<P>
So far, about 90 French teachers are sent to France and 50 to
Lome of Togo annually for training while the Center for French
Teaching and Documentation in Jos trains between 800 and 1,000
teachers every year.
</P>
<P>
Aguesse confirmed that the Nigerian government had expressed
its desire to have French as a second language in secondary
schools all over the country.
</P>
<P>
At the end of August, Comptroller-General of the Nigeria
Immigration Service Alhaji Sahabi Dange disclosed that all
immigration officials of Nigeria are to study French language to
enhance their ability to communicate with foreign nationals
coming into the country.
</P>
<P>
As most member countries of the Economic Community of West
African States (ECOWAS) have French as their official language,
the Nigerian government endeavors to enhance French-speaking
ability of its people in order to promote cooperation with its
neighboring countries in the sub-region. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980925.0121 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hong Kong Stocks Close 1.7 Percent Lower </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, September 25 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong stocks slipped
Friday after rising for three consecutive trading days, to end
the week barely above 7,700 points.
</P>
<P>
The blue chip index retreated 133 points, or 1.7 percent, to
close at 7,701.61 Friday, and turnover shrank to 4.416 billion HK
dollars (566 million U.S. dollars). The decline followed an
overnight drop of some 150 points in Wall Street Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Banking shares fell steeply by about three percent or 300
points Friday, while utility, commercial and industrial counters
all lost more than one percent.
</P>
<P>
Red chips gained 1.82 percent, or 14.27 points, to end at
799.88 Friday, and H shares edged up slightly.
</P>
<P>
The benchmark Hang Seng Index jumped 330 points, or 4.4 percent
Thursday, propelled by hopes that the U.S. Federal Reserve might
cut interest rates soon. Thursday's sharp rise expanded gains over
the previous two days, when the market already advanced some 330
points, recouping the 275-point loss on Monday. 
</P>
