<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-25 10:46 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cypriot President Calls for Resumption of Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, September 25 (Xinhua) -- Cypriot President Glafcos
Clerides has called on Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf Denktash to
return to the negotiating table to find a settlement to the
protracted Cyprus problem.
</P>
<P>
The president issued the call in New York Thursday at a
gathering on "the Cyprus Question: Prospects for a Settlement,"
organized by the U.S. organization, the National Committee on
American Foreign Policy, Cyprus News Agency reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
The Cypriot president is currently in New York to attend the
U.N. General Assembly.
</P>
<P>
Clerides said that "I will be calling on Denktash to come and
join me to work together on a solution based within the
parameters of the U.N., which will be beneficial to both
communities."
</P>
<P>
He also gave his full support for contacts between Greek and
Turkish Cypriots, especially the youth, noting that the lack of
contact creates serious problems and is not a healthy basis for
the future federation.
</P>
<P>
Denktash has banned bicommunal contacts since last December
following the European Union (EU) decision to start accession
talks with the Clerides-led Cypriot government in March.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the deployment of Russian-made S-300 anti-aircraft
missiles, Clerides said "if the other side is prepared to sit
and begin negotiations on the substance of the problem on the
basis of U.N. resolutions I would suspend indefinitely the
deployment of the missiles."
</P>
<P>
"I have also said that if the other side is prepared to sit at
the negotiating table to negotiate that which the U.N. resolutions
have asked us, that is the reduction of forces and armaments, I
will again postpone the arrival of the missiles until we agree to
a reduction of arms."
</P>
<P>
Clerides, however, stressed that "failing that, I will not
agree to any postponement simply because I am threatened by
Turkey."
</P>
<P>
Cyprus struck a deal with Russia last year to buy S-300
missile system in a bid to boost its air defense.
</P>
<P>
The deal was opposed by the U.S.-led western countries, and
triggered threats from Turkey which vowed to strike the missiles
if they are deployed on the island.
</P>
<P>
Under the international pressure, the Cypriot government has
already postponed the delivery of the missiles from August until
November this year.
</P>
<P>
Clerides emphasised the need for the international community
to exert pressure on the Turkish side, saying that the prospects
for finding a solution in Cyprus depend on how actively the
international community in particular the U.S. would act in making
Turkey realize that "it must abide with the will of the
international community and negotiate sincerely within the
parameters the U.N. Security Council has set."
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has remained divided since 1974 when Turkey landed its
troops and took over the northern third of the island after a
failed coup by Greek Cypriots seeking union with Greece.
</P>
<P>
Turkey has maintained a 35,000-strong force in northern
Cyprus, which was declared in 1983 by Turkish Cypriots as
"Turkish Republic of Northern Cyprus", recognized only by
Ankara. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980925.0125 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> COMESA Calls for Regional, Int'l Trade Links </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, September 25 (Xinhua) -- The Common Market for Eastern
and Southern Africa (COMESA) has urged its members to integrate
into both the regional and international markets so as to promote
economic development.
</P>
<P>
The regional body also recognized the role of the private
sector in the reconstruction of the regional economies, Zambian
Daily Mail reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
COMESA underlined the importance of economic integration and
globalization for its individual members.
</P>
<P>
"Most COMESA countries are individually too small to achieve
economies of scale in production and marketing of their products
and need to work together as a region if they are to achieve
significant levels of economic growth and compete in a world
market which is increasingly dominated by large trading blocks,"
it said.
</P>
<P>
"Economic and social forecasts for the region suggest that the
outlook for the future is promising provided member states adopt
and implement strategies which will further outward oriented
regional integration in the process of globalization," said
COMESA.
</P>
<P>
On the role of the private sector in the overall economic
strategies, COMESA said the industry marks an important component
of the process and the economic future of the eastern and
southern African region is almost totally dependent on the
performance of this sector, it said.
</P>
<P>
The regional body acknowledged the importance of foreign and
local investment in achieving economic growth, saying "although
COMESA can offer an attractively sized and harmonized market for
over 300 million people of the region, and although the region
has large mineral and agricultural wealth in which there are
exciting investment opportunities, the member states need to
continue to offer a stable and attractive political and economic
environment."
</P>
<P>
Countries that have espoused economic reform are better placed
to achieve economic progress, said COMESA, adding "structural
adjustment and economic reform at the national level make it more
likely that regional integration measures will succeed in those
countries which are no longer operating under constraints of
import substitution." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980925.0126 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> WB Puts Africa's Fate on Leadership </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, September 25 (Xinhua) -- The quality of African
leaders, especially their capacity against corruption, is
critical to Africa's future economic success, the just-released
World Bank's annual report said.
</P>
<P>
"Africa's leaders hold the key to the success of the
continent's economic, social and political growth and stability,"
claimed the report issued worldwide Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"A number of its (African) leaders have recognized the
stranglehold that corruption has on development efforts.
Countries including Uganda, Tanzania, Ethiopia, Benin and Malawi
have requested help from the bank to establish national
anti-corruption programs," said the report.
</P>
<P>
"When corruption has threatened to undermine development
objectives, the bank has made its views public. In some
countries, corruption has been a central feature of country
assistance program discussions," it noted.
</P>
<P>
The bank also spelt out more clearly than previously that
those African governments which are seen to be accountable and
transparent in their dealings will be receiving aid support in
the future.
</P>
<P>
"Growing evidence that the impact of development assistance is
most effective in countries that pursue sound economic policies
has guided the bank to be increasingly selective in its lending,"
the report said.
</P>
<P>
It recogniz that Africa's leaders face "tough challenges"
before they can succeed in deepening macro-economic stabilization
programs and "re-shaping the role of the state by improving
capacity to manage resources, ensuring delivery of social
services and creating attractive business environments."
</P>
<P>
One key issue, stressed the report, is the importance of
attracting new investment, not only from abroad but from Africans
with assets abroad.
</P>
<P>
The World Bank said it is estimated that some 37 percent of
all African assets are now held abroad, far higher than any other
region.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the bank said, it also needs "to be more flexible
in developing true partnerships with African nations." The
bank's lending to Africa rose by nearly two-thirds last year to
2.87 billion U.S. Dollars.
</P>
<P>
Out of 37 sub-Saharan African states, 21 recorded positive per
capita income growth rates of five percent or more last year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
