<DOCNO> XIE19980925.0127 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> No Middle East Economic Summit in 1998: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, September 25 (Xinhua) -- The World Economic Forum
will not sponsor a Middle East and North Africa economic summit
this year due to the stalled peace process, the Israeli daily The
Jerusalem Post Friday quoted a top forum official as saying.
</P>
<P>
"We don't think that the region would feel comfortable this
year having a summit as in the past. What was a product four
years ago isn't suited for this year," Gregory Blatt, director of
the Geneva-based organization, told the paper in an interview.
</P>
<P>
Instead of holding a MENA summit, the forum will highlight the
Middle East region in its annual January gathering in Davos,
Switzerland, Blatt said. Middle East businessmen on the chief
executive officer (CEO) level will be invited to take part, he
said.
</P>
<P>
This is a break from the format of the previous regional
conferences, held first in Casablanca, Morocco, in 1994 and
subsequently in Amman, Cairo, and last year in Doha, Qatar.
</P>
<P>
The Doha conference, which was downgraded to a
ministerial-level gathering from a summit due to boycotts from a
number of Arab countries, disbanded without deciding on a venue
for the next parley. None of the possible sponsors volunteered to
host the event.
</P>
<P>
An Israeli official said the failure to hold the economic
summit this year is a "punishment to the region as a whole."
There were a few Arab countries willing to host the event, but
they were pressured by strong Arab governments that did not want
the conference to take place this year, he said.
</P>
<P>
But "this is not the end of the MENA process," the official
said, noting that there is a chance the conference could convene
again in 1999 if the peace process gets back on track.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
