<HEADLINE> S. Africa Welcomes Pakistan's Ban on Nuclear </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, September 25 (Xinhua) -- South Africa Friday
welcomed Pakistan's decision to sign the nuclear test ban treaty,
and India's announcement that it was ready to conclude
discussions in this regard.
</P>
<P>
In his statement available here, South African Foreign
Minister Alfred Nzo described the decisions of Pakistan and India
as "positive developments which the world has been waiting to
hear."
</P>
<P>
The two countries' signing and ratification of the test ban
treaty is important for the early entry into force of the treaty,
Nzo noted.
</P>
<P>
Indian Prime Minister Atal Bihari Vajpayee told the United
Nations General Assembly Thursday that his country wanted the
treaty to go into force no later than September 1999.
</P>
<P>
Prior to Vajpayee's announcement, his Pakistani counterpart
Nawaz Sharif said Wednesday that his country was ready to adhere
to the nuclear test ban treaty, but that would depend on whether
India resumes its tests.
</P>
<P>
The two south Asian countries conducted a series of nuclear
tests in May, which were condemned by South Africa and many other
countries in the world. 
</P>
</TEXT>
