<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 2 Missing, 8 Injured in Plant Explosions in Australia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, September 25 (Xinhua) -- Two people were missing and
eight injured in a series of gas plant explosions in Australia's
Victoria state, and all industry and home owners in the state were
ordered to stop using gas Friday night.
</P>
<P>
Police have evacuated houses within a 5 kilometer radius of the
plant, the state's main source of gas, because of fears that
200,000-litre containers of propane could explode, the Australian
Associated Press (AAP) reported.
</P>
<P>
But the AAP did not say how many houses or residents were
involved in the evacuation.
</P>
<P>
A huge fire continued to rage through an Esso plant Friday
night, in south-eastern Victoria near Sale, about 170 kilometers
southwest of Melbourne, after a series of explosions brought the
state's gas supply to a virtual halt.
</P>
<P>
"The situation is extremely serious - all industry and all
large customers have been instructed to turn off their gas," said
David Guthrie-Jones, spokesman for the Victorian Energy Networks
Corporation (VENCorp), the state's gas transmission system
operator.
</P>
<P>
"All domestic consumers must also turn off gas appliances -
particularly any heating and cooking appliances."
</P>
<P>
He said these restrictions would allow central emergency
services, such as hospitals and nursing homes, to maintain gas
supplies.
</P>
<P>
Five explosions ripped through the Esso plant at about 12:30
p.m. Friday, setting off a series of fires which burnt unabated
and consumed a significant element of the plant.
</P>
<P>
The fires were so large that firefighters from local
firefighting department and the plant had been forced to withdraw
to devise the best plan to fight it.
</P>
<P>
Peter Morris, a television reporter from Channel Seven nearing
the scene in a helicopter, said the fire could be seen from about
30 kilometers away.  
</P>
</TEXT>
