<DOCNO> XIE19980925.0141 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-25 09:46 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Barzani: New Phase Starts in Northern Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, September 25 (Xinhua) -- Massoud Barzani, leader of
the Kurdistan Democratic Party (KDP) has said that the peace
accord signed last week between his group and another Kurdish
faction opens "a new phase" in northern Iraq.
</P>
<P>
In an exclusive interview with the English newspaper Daily
News, which was published Friday, Barzani said that the document
signed between himself and the Patriotic Union of Kurdistan (PUK)
Chairman Jalal Talaban is of great significance as it officially
ends the bloody conflicts between the KDP and PUK, two powerful
Kurdish factions in northern Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Stating that he and Talabani had agreed to establish a
"regional authority" and not a central government in northern
Iraq, Barzani noted that an eventual settlement should be reached
within the framework of ensuring Iraq's territorial integrity.
</P>
<P>
"What we are saying is that we need to have a solution for the
future with a central government within the territorial integrity
of Iraq, a solution that would be acceptable to our people," he
said.
</P>
<P>
Barzani and Talabani reached a peace agreement in Washington
on September 18 under the auspices of U.S. State Department
officials, which is an important step in resolving the knotty
northern Iraq problem.
</P>
<P>
The peace accord sets forth a timetable for reconciliation and
revival of a unified, regional administration based on the rule
of law and democracy.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, it also contains provisions for regional elections,
revenue sharing based on the needs of the population and
assurance of security for the borders.
</P>
<P>
The pro-Turkey KDP and PUK allegedly backed by Iran have been
fighting for the control of northern Iraq which has become a
power vacuum as a result of the Saddam Hussein regime's defeat in
the 1991 Gulf War.
</P>
<P>
With regard to the implementation of the peace accord, Barzani
said that he would meet with Talabani in Ankara in early November
to decide on the concrete measures to that effect.
</P>
<P>
While hailing the signing of the KDP-PUK accord, Turkey has
once again stressed that the northern Iraq issue should be solved
on the basis of the territorial integrity of Iraq.
</P>
<P>
"The whole problem is to fill the authority vacuum in northern
Iraq. An ultimate settlement should definitely be based on Iraq's
territorial integrity," a Turkish Foreign Ministry spokesman told
a press conference last week. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980925.0142 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Africa Tops WB's Investments to Private Sector </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, September 25 (Xinhua) -- Africa, compared to other
regions, has the largest number of projects approved this year by
the International Finance Corporation (IFC), the lending arm of
the World Bank to the private sector.
</P>
<P>
Thus it reflects the World Bank's priority of working in
developing countries, the bank's annual report released worldwide
Thursday shows.
</P>
<P>
There were commitments for 54 projects with 81 projects
approved for amounts of 33.5 billion Shillings (558.3 million
U.S. Dollars) and 40.7 billion Shillings (678 million Dollars)
respectively across the continent.
</P>
<P>
The thrust of the work in Africa was in mobilizing and
allocating domestic savings by creating a better-developed
financial structure particularly in Ghana and Cote d'Ivoire as
well as expanding local entrepreneurship and building
infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
Michael Hooper, IFC head of Nairobi office, said Thursday that
despite the financial crisis in Asia which will curb IFC's
investment portfolio, the corporation intends to remain a major
player in the promotion of projects aimed at helping reduce
unemployment and poverty in Africa.
</P>
<P>
In the coming fiscal year, IFC would set up hubs in Nairobi,
Johannesburg and Abidjan to strengthen its ability to work on the
ground and implement larger projects than the ones it is
currently authorized to do, he said.
</P>
<P>
Hooper urged African countries to learn from the experience of
the Asian crisis on the importance of transparency and the way
business is done, noting that Africa suffers directly from the
crisis through reduced prices of primary commodities.
</P>
<P>
This year, IFC invested in two hospitals and a charcoal
producer that will use the invasive wattle tree as raw material
in South Africa.
</P>
<P>
Hooper said the corporation also invested in the first modern
bulk grain handling and storage facility in Kenya's Indian Ocean
port of Mombasa this year.
</P>
<P>
However, he said IFC was disappointed with the slow pace of
privatization in Kenya, adding that the country is lagging behind
Uganda and Tanzania in privatization and urged the government to
speed up the process. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
