<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lebanon's Flight Attendants to Stage Strike </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, September 25 (Xinhua) -- Almost 400 flight attendants
of Lebanon's national carrier Middle East Airlines (MEA) have
approved their first ever strike to protest against the company's
refusal to meet their demands.
</P>
<P>
After a general assembly meeting at the company's headquarters
on Thursday, MEA's cabin crew personnel decided to take the step,
without specifying the exact date or duration of the protest
action, the Daily Star reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
"This is the first time we've called a strike, but we won't say
when until a day before," head of the flight attendants' union
Robert Feghali told the paper.
</P>
<P>
The union signed a labor agreement in January this year with
the previous MEA board chaired by Khaled Salam, who has since
resigned after allegations that he was involved in the fraudulent
leasing of three Airbuses from Singapore Airlines.
</P>
<P>
The agreement stipulated that flight attendants should receive
a 20 percent salary increase and deserving attendants should
benefit from promotion.
</P>
<P>
Feghali said that new MEA Chairman Mohammed Hout refused to
recognise the employees' right to move up the promotional ladder
and only agreed to increase the portion of their salaries.
</P>
<P>
He added that if the protest action failed to achieve the
union's demands, they would turn to the government which will
then appoint an arbitration committee to issue a final decision
binding on both sides.
</P>
<P>
MEA, 99 percent of which is owned by the country's central
bank, has been beset with financial and managerial problems in
recent years with its 1997 losses reaching 53 million
U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
In July, the company's pilots staged a similar strike causing
loss of over 1.25 million dollars for the airline. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
