<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Analysts Optimistic About Hong Kong's Economy Recovery </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 25 (Xinhua) -- After this year's
difficulties, a gradual economic recovery is expected in Hong Kong
in the next two years, if Hong Kong makes full use of its own
advantages and possible changes in the overall economy, some
Beijing analysts say.
</P>
<P>
They say that, having experienced the negative effects of the
Asian financial crisis, the government of the Hong Kong Special
Administrative Region (SAR) and local people face three
challenges: financial stability, economic recovery and economic
restructuring.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong's economy suffered a serious decline this year
because of the regional financial crisis and economic bubble, and
international speculators used the opportunity to cause further
turbulence in Hong Kong's financial market. The SAR government
adopted some countermeasures to protect the stability of the
financial market, which won wide support from the public and
raised confidence.
</P>
<P>
Zheng Jingping, vice-director of the State Statistics Bureau's
International Statistics and Information Center, says that Hong
Kong is an international free port with well-developed service and
trade industries and that tertiary industry accounts for over 80
percent of its gross national product.
</P>
<P>
There are indications that the outside environment of Hong
Kong's economy will have some positive changes, he said.
</P>
<P>
In Zheng's view, the Chinese mainland and the United States are
Hong Kong's top two trade partners. So far this year the mainland
has managed to maintain economic growth at above seven percent and
that eight percent for the year is possible. Economic growth in
the U.S. is estimated to be about 2.9 percent this year. The
steady development of the two trade partners will help Hong Kong's
recovery.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980925.0148 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hong Kong Economic Recovery (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Recent analyses by many international economic and financial
institutions indicate that the economies and currencies of Asian
countries are bottoming out, which will benefit Hong Kong's export
and tourism industry.
</P>
<P>
Zheng says that the strength of the U.S. Dollar is being
challenged by the Euro and and gradual recovery of the Japanese
Yen and other Asian currencies and that a devaluation of the
U.S. Dollar is inevitable. As a result, the Hong Kong Dollar,
which is pegged to the U.S. Dollar, will also devalue, which will
help Hong Kong's trade and tourism as well.
</P>
<P>
Analysts in Beijing say that the fundamentals of Hong Kong's
economy are still very good. With its highly-developed free market
mechanism, strong capital, legal system and outstanding management
personnel, Hong Kong will remain an ideal place for international
investment.
</P>
<P>
Economist Wei Jianing says that Hong Kong's financial industry
is well developed and has a broad line of fund-raising tools. When
its capital advantage is combined with the science and technology
of the mainland, it is possible that Hong Kong could become a
Silicon Valley of China or even Asia.
</P>
<P>
Wei, who is director of the State Council Development Research
Center's Financial Research Institute, says that high-tech risk
investment could turn speculative funds in Hong Kong's financial
market into investment funds and short-term capital into long-term
capital.
</P>
<P>
A view shared by these economists is that Hong Kong's economic
restructuring will be painful but that restructuring is
beneficial for clearing the bubble and increasing Hong Kong's
competitiveness and that this will provide a solid foundation for
the recovery. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
