<DOCNO> XIE19980925.0149 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Share Prices Plunge in Tokyo on Wall Street Falling </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, September 25 (Xinhua) -- Stock prices tumbled in Tokyo
Friday after the near-collapse of a major U.S. hedge fund sent share
prices on Wall Street falling overnight.
</P>
<P>
The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues on the First
Section of the Tokyo Stock Exchange lost 481.94 points, or 3.39
percent, to close at 13,723.84 and easily erased Thursday's 3.02
percent gain.
</P>
<P>
The broader-based Tokyo Stock Price Index (TOPIX), covering all
First Section issues, dropped 28.08 points or 2.60 percent to
1,049.93.
</P>
<P>
Turnover on the major section decreased to an estimated 370 million
shares from Thursday's 460 million shares.
</P>
<P>
Steel maker NKK was the day's most heavily traded issue.
</P>
<P>
Traders said the euphoria felt throughout the world equity markets
Thursday over a possible cut in U.S. interest rates vanished as New
York's Dow Jones industrial index plunged 1.87 percent on news that 15
major international banks have come to the rescue of Long-Term Capital
Management L.P., a high-flying hedge fund that is on the verge of
collapse.
</P>
<P>
Financial issues were hit hard on news that the Japanese government
is not in favor of using public money to help the Long-Term Credit
Bank of Japan (LTCB) waive its loan claims on nonbank affiliates.
</P>
<P>
The news regarding LTCB depressed investors because it means the
ailing corporate lender may have a harder time clearing away its
problem loans, something it must do to merge with Sumitomo Trust and
Banking.
</P>
<P>
Of the 1,342 issues listed on the First Section, losers overwhelmed
gainers 1,004 to 177, with 114 issues ending unchanged. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980925.0150 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenya's Troubled Bank May Be Re-Opened </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, September 25 (Xinhua) -- Normal banking operations
may soon resume at the Trust Bank, Kenya's seventh biggest
commercial bank which was put under statutory management due to a
run by depositors last week.
</P>
<P>
A rescue package has been put in place to re-activate the
bank, the Daily Nation newspaper reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
"We foresee the bank re-opening for normal banking business
very soon," said Michael Muhindi, Trust Bank's interim manager
who was appointed by the Central Bank of Kenya.
</P>
<P>
Muhindi asked Thursday all deposit customers of the bank to
immediately contact their respective branches for a copy of the
proposed new depositors' agreement, which they should complete as
required and "expeditiously return to the branch".
</P>
<P>
However, he did not reveal further details over the rescue
work.
</P>
<P>
First to be put under the statutory management of the Central
Bank of Kenya (CBK) was Reliance Bank Limited which was accused
by the CBK of issuing checks worth 304 million Shillings (about
5.07 million U.S. Dollars) which were not backed by deposits.
</P>
<P>
Four directors of the Reliance Bank and five businessmen were
subsequently arraigned in court charged with fraud earlier this
month.
</P>
<P>
Trust Bank, was taken over by the CBK after it suffered run by
depositors when it failed to honor checks amounting to 360
million Shillings (about 6 million U.S. Dollars). The bank had
for long been locked in a legal tussle with a private company.
</P>
<P>
The Bullion Bank was taken over last Friday because of a
600-million-Shilling (10 million U.S. Dollars) debt. The three
banks have closed down since being put under control of the
central bank.
</P>
<P>
A following move by the CBK to restore depositor confidence,
in particular among the small banks through a salvage program,
has stemmed the seeming mass run by depositors.
</P>
<P>
The CBK has called an emergency meeting of the banks' top
officers to map out strategies at keeping them afloat.
</P>
<P>
Banking sources view the rescue package put in place for Trust
Bank as part of the proceedings of the meeting and are optimistic
other banks put under statutory management may bounce back into
business. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980925.0151 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> PTA Bank to Expand Capital Base </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, September 25 (Xinhua) -- The Preferential Trade Area
(PTA) Bank is to increase its capital base from the current 500
million to five billion U.S. Dollars in the next century, Zambia
Daily Mail said Friday.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with the paper in Lusaka Thursday, Hardy
Pemhiwa, the bank's director of information and technology, said
that the PTA Bank hoped to meet the target by expanding its
services to cater for a wider market.
</P>
<P>
"The bank is growing from strength to strength and we are now
intending to capture a bigger client-base to include non-members
of the Common Market for Eastern and Southern Africa (COMESA),"
he said.
</P>
<P>
"Our target is to increase the capital base to about five
billion from 500 million Dollars in the next millennium," Pemhiwa
observed.
</P>
<P>
He added that the bank was further considering increasing the
ceiling for loan disbursements to customers.
</P>
<P>
PTA is the predecessor of the existing 20-member COMESA which
is located in Lusaka, capital of Zambia.
</P>
<P>
The Burundi-based PTA Bank was founded in 1986 and its
operations include financing PTA projects and trade-related
activities and managing PTA travelers' checks.
</P>
<P>
Together with COMESA's Trade Information Network, the
Automated System of Customs Data, the Clearing House and other
organs, PTA Bank will facilitate the economic integration in
eastern and southern Africa. 
</P>
</TEXT>
