<HEADLINE> Major Australian Parties Vie For One Nation Preferences </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, September 25 (Xinhua) -- Australia's two rivaling big
political parties, the ruling Liberal Party and the opposition
Australian Labor Party, Friday appealed to Pauline Hanson's One
Nation Party supporters for their second preferences in a bid to
win the October 3 election.
</P>
<P>
The moves came with the latest opinion survey showing One
Nation Party preferences would be crucial to the election outcome.
</P>
<P>
Australian Prime Minister John Howard Friday conceded his
government was in danger of losing and warned that the Labor Party
could scrape into power on the back of One Nation Party
preferences.
</P>
<P>
Under the nation's preferential voting system, voters are
required to rank candidates in order of preference, and to be
elected, a candidate must achieve an absolute majority, namely at
least 50 percent plus one vote, either on first preference or
following distribution of preference votes.
</P>
<P>
If no candidate has won an absolute majority, preferences are
allocated, starting with those of the least-supported candidate,
until an absolute majority is obtained.
</P>
<P>
The latest A.C. Nielsen poll shows support for the ruling
coalition has fallen a point to 41 percent, trailing the Labor
Party's 43 percent. Once the likely preferences are taken into
account, the Labor Party is on 52 percent and the coalition on 48
percent.
</P>
<P>
"Now I would say to One Nation voters... I don't agree with the
policies of the party that you are proposing to vote for, I don't
think they have anything to offer, but when you cast your vote
think of your preference," Howard told Melbourne radio 3AW.
</P>
<P>
"I quite unashamedly want the preference vote of all minor
parties, or the voters of all minor parties, not the minor parties
themselves."
</P>
<P>
Opposition leader Kim Beazley accused Howard of hypocrisy and
said the Labor Party had always argued for voters' preferences but
had never done a deal with One Nation.
</P>
<P>
But Gary Gray, secretary of the Labor Party's national
secretary, made his own appeal to One Nation supporters to vote
against the ruling party by directing preferences to Labor.
</P>
<P>
Lynton Crosby, campaign director of the Liberal Party, admitted
the election is tight and every vote would count.
</P>
<P>
Support in Australia for the racist One Nation Party, founded
by Pauline Hanson last year, averages 6 percent, recent opinion
surveys have found. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
