<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigerian Leader Calls for Lift of Sanctions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, September 25 (Xinhua) -- Nigerian military leader
General Abdulsalam Abubakar has appealed to the international
community to lift sanctions against his country as demonstration
of its support for the on-going democratization process.
</P>
<P>
Abubakar made the call Thursday in New York when he addressed
the 53rd session of the United Nations General Assembly.
</P>
<P>
In his address, Abubakar reiterated his government's
commitment to handing over power to a democratically elected
civilian administration on May 29, 1999.
</P>
<P>
He said the current changes in the country could best be
described as a "silent but peaceful revolution" and called on
Nigerians still on self-exile to return and join the
democratization process.
</P>
<P>
Abubakar stressed his government's commitment to respect for
human rights, adding that the government's promise on
de-congestion of prisons was in line with its avowed commitment
in that regard.
</P>
<P>
Nigeria was sanctioned by the West after the annulment of the
June 12, 1993 presidential election. Further sanctions were
imposed in 1995 for executing author Ken Saro-Wiwa and eight
other minority activists.
</P>
<P>
Its relations with the West, however, has improved since
Abubakar took office in June, as the new leader has since taken
drastic measures in promoting reconciliation, human rights and a
new transition to civil rule program.
</P>
<P>
In his speech, the general also condemned terrorism around the
world, especially the recent bombings of the United States
embassies in Kenya and Tanzania, and called for collective
efforts to stamp out the menace.
</P>
<P>
Abubakar called for the accelerated reforms of the U.N.
Security Council, saying that the democratization of the U.N. was
necessary to engender loyalty and commitment by members. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
