<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Embassy in Uganda Targeted by Terrorists: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, September 25 (Xinhua) -- Eighteen suspected
terrorists held by Ugandan security confessed that they had
targeted the U.S. embassy here the day the Nairobi and
Dar-es-Salaam embassies were blown up in early August.
</P>
<P>
The terrorist activities were backed by Sudan and Saudi
terrorist financier Osama bin Laden, Friday's New Vision daily
quoted Muruli Mukasa, the State Minister for Security, as saying
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Mukasa said the plotted bombings here were planned to be more
serious and devastating than those in Kenya and Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
The Bank of Uganda, the Post Office and a downtown market were
also targeted, the minister added.
</P>
<P>
He said the alert security personnel detected the explosives
in time, but declined to say the types and quantities of the
powerful explosives.
</P>
<P>
The suspects, including Ugandans and Somalis who allegedly
received financial backing, training and other facilitation from
Khartoum and Osama bin Laden, will be produced in courts soon
after investigations.
</P>
<P>
The Ugandan Somalis recently arrested include a Sheikh
Abdulayi. However, there is confirmation in the report that
Sheikh Abdulayi was the Ugandan sheikh recently said to have been
trained in Sudan under Laden.
</P>
<P>
A police commander said the suspects will only be extradited
if the U.S. government requests the Uganda Judicial Service to do
so because Kampala has no extradition agreement with Washington.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
