<HEADLINE> Chinese Vice-Premier Meets With Former Panamanian FM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 25 (Xinhua) -- Vice-Premier Qian Qichen said
here today that he believes the Sino-Panamanian relations will
make new progress at the turn of the century.
</P>
<P>
Qian made the remarks while meeting with Oyden Ortega, former
Foreign Minister of Panama.
</P>
<P>
Qian said that there have been frequent exchanges between China
and Panama and that bilateral trade dates back to ancient times.
</P>
<P>
The Panama Canal is an important link between the Pacific Ocean
and the Atlantic, he said, and China, as an important user of the
canal, has always supported Panama's efforts to recover it and
hopes that it can be a canal of Panama.
</P>
<P>
Qian said he hopes the two sides further increase exchanges
and strengthen cooperation in the economic and cultural sectors.
</P>
<P>
Ortega, who is also chairman of the foreign affairs committee of
Panama's Parliament, said that the members of his delegation have
been impressed by China's rapid development, and his country
appreciates China's support on the canal issue.
</P>
<P>
He said that the Panamanian Parliament hopes to develop
friendly ties with China's National People's Congress.
</P>
<P>
The delegation, which is here as guest of the Chinese People's
Institute of Foreign Affairs, is scheduled to visit Xi'an,
Shanghai and Shenzhen. 
</P>
</TEXT>
