<HEADLINE> Algeria Skips Chess Olympiad </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ALGIERS, September 24 (Xinhua) -- Algeria has decided to skip
the 33rd chess Olympiad slated no September 26 in Elista, Russia,
local reports said on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Algerian Youth and Sports Department was quoted as saying that
Algeria was forced to skip the tournament as it will cost a
accommodation fee of 33,000 US dollars.
</P>
<P>
However, Algeria was still to compete in the Chess World
Championships slated in October in Spain.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, Algeria also failed to show up for the 32nd chess
Olympiad in Armenia after it finished 64th in the 1994 Olympiad
which had the participation of 120 squads. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980925.0169 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Foreigners In Beijing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 25 (Xinhua) -- Armin Wolfgang Lang, a German
executive with Beijing Holiday Inn Crown Plaza, has a lot to say
about his life in China.
</P>
<P>
"More than ten years ago when I first came to Beijing, local
people usually looked at me as if they were looking at a monkey,"
he says, but "Now, I can walk leisurely in the streets."
</P>
<P>
More than a decade ago, Lang had to go to the Beijing
Friendship Store, which was designated for foreigners, to get
things he wanted. But still he felt that the goods were not good
enough for such a special shop.
</P>
<P>
Now, he says, "We foreigners can buy goods at any stores which
have plenty of commodities."
</P>
<P>
There are some 30,000 foreigners in the Chinese capital and
more than 2 million overseas visitors annually. Although they
account for only a small part of the Beijing's 13 million
residents, they have a large impact on the urban landscape.
</P>
<P>
In the eastern part of the city, there are communities of
foreigners, with markets, restaurants, bars, schools, clinics and
recreation facilities catering to the special interest group.
</P>
<P>
Lang usually takes a walk to the Forbidden City, the imperial
residence of emperors of the Ming (1368-1644) and Qing (1644-1911)
dynasties. The museum there is a little more than two kilometers
from the Beijing Holiday Inn Crown Plaza. He said he loves to chat
with local people and even invites them to his home.
</P>
<P>
In the past, ordinary Chinese people were not allowed to have
contact with foreigners individually, let alone invite them into
their homes. But, this is a thing of the past. At present, there
are about 800 people in Beijing marrying foreigners each year.
</P>
<P>
There are also nearly 200,000 well-educated Chinese working in
foreign-funded enterprises in the Chinese capital.
</P>
<P>
Liu Chengshe, of the Beijing Public Security Bureau, says that
foreigners will feel freer in Beijing. In the past foreigners
coming to Beijing had to go through many procedures before getting
visas, now it is much simpler. And restrictions on areas in Beijng
where foreigners can visit have also been cancelled, he says.
</P>
<P>
Foreigners also now pay the same amount as Chinese for tickets
to tourist spots.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980925.0170 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. African Rand's Rally Raises Hopes for Rate Cut </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, September 25 (Xinhua) -- A strengthening Rand
has pushed fears of a recession into the background and raised
hopes for an interest rate cut, local media reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
The Rand reached its best level at 5.76 against the U.S.
Dollar Thursday, up from a low of 6.40 in July.
</P>
<P>
South African industrial and financial shares were driven
higher by a rebounding currency in moderate trade on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
If the strengthening of the currency continued, interest rates
would begin to fall, allowing the country to escape a full-blown
recession, The Star newspaper quoted Econometrix chief economist
Azar Jammine as saying.
</P>
<P>
"At some point, speculators have to borrow Rands. If the Rand
is made sufficiently expensive, as our Reserve Bank has done, the
cost of paying interest on borrowed Rand exceeds the profits they
hope to make," said Jammine.
</P>
<P>
The prime lending rate of commercial banks now stands at 25.5
percent.
</P>
<P>
"One reason could be that speculators are disillusioned, and
are now buying back the Rand they've sold and cutting their
losses, creating a demand.
</P>
<P>
"Exporters bring more Rand back into the country before it
strengthens further. They're scared the Rand might rise and try
to rush out and get it at today's rate before they get fewer Rand
for their Dollars."
</P>
<P>
Jammine said the government and exporters did not want to see
the Rand remain too strong for too long because the gold price in
the Rand would start to fall. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980925.0171 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shanghai Welcomes Foreign Investment to Build Old-Folks Homes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, September 25 (Xinhua) -- The leading Chinese
industrial city of Shanghai will institute preferential
measures to induce domestic and foreign investment in building
more old folks homes.
</P>
<P>
Vice-mayor Feng Guoqin said the municipal government has
adopted a regulation to encourage the building of more of these
facilities in this city where one out of every three residents
will be elderly by the year 2025.
</P>
<P>
This regulation, which becomes effective on October 1, welcomes
enterprises, government bodies, social organizations and
individuals to invest in the building of old-folks homes.
</P>
<P>
The city will provide preferential policies for non-profit
old-folks homes in the areas of taxes and fees collections.
</P>
<P>
The vice mayor said profit-making old-folks homes will be
allowed to set prices themselves.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai has 2.34 million people over 60 years of age,
accounting for 17.8 percent of its total population.
</P>
<P>
Experts predict that the aged population in the city will reach
4.69 million in 2025, which will then be 33 percent for the total
population.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
