<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Eight Injured In Gas Plant Explosion in Australia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, September 25 (Xinhua) -- Eight people were injured in
a series of explosions Friday at a big gas plant in Australia's
Victoria state, leaving the state's gas supplies under threat.
</P>
<P>
Five explosions ripped through the Esso plant near Sale, about
170 kilometers southwest of Melbourne, at about 12:30 p.m. (local
time), setting off a series of fires which were burning unabated
and consuming a significant element of the plant, the state's main
source of gas.
</P>
<P>
The fires were so large that firefighters from local fire
fighting department and the plant had been forced to withdraw to
devise the best plan to fight it, the Australian Associated Press
reported.
</P>
<P>
One person was critically injured with severe facial and body
burns.
</P>
<P>
Peter Morris, a television reporter from Channel Seven nearing
the scene in a helicopter, said the fires could be seen from about
30 kilometers away.
</P>
<P>
"It's a very large fireball probably two or three square
kilometers in size," Morris told local radio 3AW.
</P>
<P>
"As we approached the scene from about 30 kilometers away we
could see a large plume of thick black smoke probably rising about
15 kilometers into the air."
</P>
<P>
Three major fires were still burning out of control at 3:30
p.m. and a large storage tank was drenched by sprayers so that it
did not get too hot, local fire fighting department spokesman
Peter Philp said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Victoria Energy Networks Corporation (VENCorp),
the state's gas transmission system operator, warned that domestic
supplies would be severely restricted if the problem was not
quickly resolved.
</P>
<P>
VENCorp said no gas was coming ashore from Bass Strait, and an
Esso spokesman confirmed a temporary shutdown of gas and crude oil
supplies during the emergency.
</P>
<P>
"There is only the gas in the pipelines to maintain supplies,"
a statement issued by VENCorp said.
</P>
<P>
A local police spokesman said the cause of the explosions was
not known.
</P>
<P>
This is the second time this year that gas supplies from the
Esso plant have been affected.
</P>
<P>
In June, a 10-meter ice plug blocked the main supply line into
the plant, which is Victoria's major source of natural gas.
</P>
<P>
State-wide restrictions were imposed at the time, forcing
factory closures in 100 industry sectors at an estimated cost of
30 million U.S. dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
