<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Istanbul Mayor: Conviction Not to End His </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, September 25 (Xinhua) -- Turkey's pro-Islamic Istanbul
Mayor Tayip Erdogan has declared that the 10-month prison sentence
would not deter him from continuing his political career, local
Daily News reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a crowded press conference at the Istanbul
municipality building Thursday, Erdogan said that "this is the
wrong decision. The public conscience has found me not guilty. This
unjust ruling has opened a new era. A new struggle has begun."
</P>
<P>
Turkey's Supreme Court of Appeals Wednesday upheld the
sentence for Erdogan and the court decision will go to the
Interior Ministry, which will ask the Council of State to end
Erdogan's tenure as mayor.
</P>
<P>
The 45-year-old mayor was found guilty by the State Security
Court in Diyarbakir, southeast Turkey in April "for inciting
hatred based on religious differences" in a speech at a political
rally last year.
</P>
<P>
"Our mosques are our barracks, our minarets are our bayonets,
our domes are our helmets and our believers are our soldiers,"
Erdogan said at the rally, reading from a poem by nationalist poet
Ziya Gokalp.
</P>
<P>
Outside of the municipality building, over 30,000 supporters
blocked streets and chanted anti-government slogans to protest
the conviction.
</P>
<P>
"The ruling is a tragedy in the history of our justice
system. It casts the shadow of politics on the courts," Erdogan
said in front of his supporters.
</P>
<P>
Chief Prosecutor Vural Savas has already asked the appeals
court to act with speed to uphold the verdict and accused Erdogan
of being a "cheap bully."
</P>
<P>
Erdogan was elected mayor in March 1994 on the Islamist
Welfare Party (RP) ticket. When the RP was shut down in January
this year, he joined the Islamist Virtue Party (FP). 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
