<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lu Yufu, a Rising Star to World Podium </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
By Sportswriter Shi Ting
</P>
<P>
TIANJIN, September 25 (Xinhua) -- For the time being, Lu Yufu
is the gymnast most talked about in the Chinese Cup
International, not because he is emerging as a new gold medal
reaper of the ever-growing Chinese gymnastics.
</P>
<P>
Truly, he's yet to claim a major title to his credit, Lu Yufu
is nevertheless the odds-on hot candidate most likely to deliver
the best.
</P>
<P>
"Lu is the strongest amidst the new generation of the Chinese
men gymnasts," head coach Huang Yubin said, "he is the man tipped
to become the right successor to Li Xiaoshuang."
</P>
<P>
Two years ago in Atlanta, the United States, Li Xiaoshuang
awarded China its first-ever all-round Olympic gold medal with
his superb triumph over Russian legendary Alexei Nemov.
</P>
<P>
In Lu's ability, Huang said he has deep belief even though his
protege was still to botch up his chances at the China Cup
International which was going on here in the Tianjin Sports
Center, the venue for the next year's world championships.
</P>
<P>
In the last rotation of the all-round battle last night, Lu
sat down on his much-hyped vault, which is waiting to be named
after him, for a modest 9.125. The result dragged him to the
fourth place in the overall standings and costed him the berth
for tonight's apparatus finals.
</P>
<P>
"If I stuck, I could win," Lu said after his unique
"handspring sideways 2 1/2 tucked back salto" vaulting which he
originated and displayed for the first time in the Goodwill Games
in New York this summer.
</P>
<P>
The courage to perform the most incredible vault touched the
hearts of the entire gymnastic community, especially after Sang
Lang's tragic fall in a practice vault at the Games broke the
17-year-old's neck and left her paralyzed in hospital.
</P>
<P>
"I was shocked and then very much moved," Gao Jian,
vice-president of the Chinese Gymnastics Association (CGA) said,
"It's a real commitment for him to stick with the routine."
</P>
<P>
"Lu is a very brave man indeed," former triple Olympic
champion Li Ning echoed.
</P>
<P>
"I just go out and do my best and put everything else aside,"
Lu said, "I don't allow myself to get into what-ifs."
</P>
<P>
The popularity for the 20-year-old Cantonese around here is
evident. The stadium bursted into gusts of applauses when he took
the floor and performed his tricks as technically sound and
artistically pleasant.
</P>
<P>
"He has the calibre of skills, and now he just needs to
perfect them," Gao Jian said, noting that improving consistency
is the biggest hurdle for Lu to cross over.
</P>
<P>
In fact, Lu has made considerable progresses. In the national
championships prior to the China Cup, Lu hit three of his four
vaults and earned a meet-high 9.85 to his merit.
</P>
<P>
"This was probably his best meet in terms of hitting
percentage," Gao said.
</P>
<P>
But what counts best is to peak when what matters most, saying
the Asian Games this December, next year's Worlds and Sydney 2000
Olympics.
</P>
<P>
Maybe then Lu Yufu can prove to be a worthy successor to Li
Xiaoshuang. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
