<HEADLINE> Tanasugarn to Challenge Seles in Princess Cup Semis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, September 25 (Xinhua) - Thai ace Tamarine Tanasugarn
beat Amy Frazier of the United States here on Friday to clinch a
semi-final berth against Monica Seles in the 450,000 US dollars
WTA Princess Cup tennis tournament.
</P>
<P>
The powerful Tanasugarn chalked up a 6-1, 6-3 win over the
American who struggled against strong winds over the center court.
</P>
<P>
"It's my first tournament that I've done pretty well in Japan,
I was always here since juniors. I feel great, I just play my
best and have fun and enjoy," said 21-year-old Tanasugarn, who
also achieved a doubles semi-final berth with Elena Likhovtseva
of Russia on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"It was very windy today and it was very difficult for both of
us, so I just tried to hang in there and hit the ball into the cou
rt. I played safe today, not hitting a lot of unforced errors,"
said unseeded Tanasugarn.
</P>
<P>
Tanasugarn ended Frazier's winning streak as the latter had
beaten rising 16-year-old Croatian Mirjana Lucic and No. 3 seed
Amanda Coetzer of South Africa in the first two rounds.
</P>
<P>
In the semi-finals on Saturday, Tanasugarn will challenge
defending champion Seles, who breezed past Julie Halard-Decugis
of France 6-2, 6-1.
</P>
<P>
French Open champion Arantxa Sanchez Vicario also sailed into
the semifinals by beating Russian teenage sensation Anna
Kournikova 6-3, 6-2, her second straight win over the Russian
following her US Open fourth round win after three defeats in a
row.
</P>
<P>
The top-seeded Spaniard, who won the 1994 edition here, will
play the other semifinal against the winner between Anke Huber of
Germany and Olga Barabanschikova of Belarus. 
</P>
