<HEADLINE> IFC Provides Financing to Bangladesh's Projects </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, September 25 (Xinhua) -- The International Financial
Corporation (IFC), the private sector window of the World Bank,
has provided 227.32 million U.S. dollars to 16 private projects in
Bangladesh since 1996, the newspaper The Daily Star reported
Friday.
</P>
<P>
The IFC is quite open for more projects, mainly in power, gas
exploration and telecommunications and port development in the
country, Rashad Kaldany, the visiting IFC director for South and
Southeast Asia, was quoted as saying here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The 110-megawatt barge-mounted power plant with a total cost of
103 million dollars is one of the major IFC's projects in
Bangladesh, which started operation in the southwestern city of
Khulna on September 12.
</P>
<P>
The 45 million-dollar Lafarge Surma Cement Limited and 22.5
million-dollar Grameen (countryside) Phone are the other two major
IFC-assisted projects in the country.
</P>
<P>
The IFC investment has increased significantly every year since
1996, placing Bangladesh among the nine countries in which IFC's
investment approval exceeded 100 million dollars in 1998.
</P>
<P>
The IFC investment in Bangladesh was 15 million dollars in
1996, 45 million dollars in 1997 and 103 million dollars this
year, Kaldany stated.
</P>
<P>
"We're optimistic of development in Bangladesh in the
foreseeable future," the IFC director stated. "We are looking for
investment and we would be keen to support export-oriented
industries."
</P>
<P>
However, he pointed out that bureaucracy existing in Bangladesh
sometimes delayed getting the IFC-assisted projects moving. He
hoped to work with the government to overcome the problems.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
