<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Street Kids: Chronic Problem for Philippines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, September 25 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government has
made much effort to save the country's tens of thousands of street
children and their families in recent years. However, street
children remain a daunting issue besetting the government.
</P>
<P>
With the help of the U.N. Children's Fund (UNICEF), the
government has taken a series of measures to change the fate of
the large number of street children in the country since the
1980s.
</P>
<P>
Early this year, the government launched a major campaign to
rid Manila of street children by the year 2000 as the first step
to eliminating this fixture from the country's street.
</P>
<P>
Under the campaign, the government is trying to provide these
kids in the capital region with proper education, livelihood
opportunities and capability-building assistance.
</P>
<P>
In the latest effort to help them, President Joseph Estrada
last week ordered the Department of Social Welfare and Development
to help in the resettlement and rehabilitation of about 75,000
street children in Metro Manila alone.
</P>
<P>
Describing the plight of street children as "a deep social
wound." Estrada called on the government and the private sector to
pay serious attention to this protracted social problem.
</P>
<P>
All these efforts have been successful to a certain degree.
Over the last seven years, nearly 90,000 street children have been
put into schools, according to a report from the Department of
Social Welfare and Development.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, dozens of street children centers have been
established in major cities in the country and a network composed
of government and non-government organizations has already been
set up in the country to deal with the street children issue.
</P>
<P>
But social workers said the country still has a long way to go
to solve the problem.
</P>
<P>
According to the estimate of the social welfare department,
there are 250,000 street children in the country's major cities,
comprising about 2 percent of the country's child population. But
social workers believed their actual number may have already reach
half a million.
</P>
<P>
The country's street children phenomenon emerged as a serious
problem in the 1970s when thousands of families were forced to
flee from the rural areas to the cities to escape from the
insurgencies of some anti-government forces and the rising poverty
caused by these insurgencies.
</P>
<P>
Their arrival in the cities also marked the emergence of the
squatter phenomenon, especially in cities like Manila, Cebu in the
south and Baguio in the north.
</P>
<P>
By the 1980s, some 17 million or about a third of the country's
population were residing in the cities, most of them settling in
slums as they sought jobs and ways to survive.
</P>
<P>
From the group emerged the so-called street children who must
fend for themselves or help their families make a living. Braving
the snarl of traffic, they sell newspapers, flowers and candy, or
simply beg for their bread on the streets.
</P>
<P>
According to a study conducted by the social welfare
department, 75 percent of the street children have regular contact
with their families, 20-25 percent have families but contact is
irregular and 5 percent are those who have been completely
abandoned by their families.
</P>
<P>
A lot of social problems have arisen from the large number of
street children, the study said.
</P>
<P>
These children are easy targets to sexual abuse, prostitution,
drug abuse, street violence and criminal syndicates. Many of them
end up in orphanages, jails, sex dens and sweat shops.
</P>
<P>
Social welfare organizations, both government and
non-government, mostly the latter, have tried to cope with the
problem but with little success.
</P>
<P>
"The reason (for this) as always is the lack of money," said
Nelly Miranda, director of the National Project on Street Children
(NPSC), an organization created by the government in 1987 to
protect street kids.
</P>
<P>
Miranda said she couldn't believe her ears when she was told
the NPSC received a funding of only 4 million pesos (about 100,000
U.S. dollars) a year, part of it coming from the UNICEF.
</P>
<P>
With such a meager budget, she said, it is difficult for the
group to extend their help, such as education, training and health
service, to so many street children.
</P>
<P>
According to Miranda, only five cities in the country included
the street children problem in their development plans.
</P>
<P>
Miranda called on local governments and various quarters of the
country, especially the private sector, to take their share of
responsibility for the street children.
</P>
<P>
She also urged the government to increase budget for social
service and continue its efforts to ease poverty, a main cause for
the rising number of street children in the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
