<HEADLINE> Bangladesh to Partly Privatize National Flag Carrier </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, September 25 (Xinhua) -- The Bangladeshi government will
partially privatize the national flag carrier, Biman, by selling
its shares to an international airline and its employees
respectively.
</P>
<P>
The process of floating 49 percent of the shares of Biman is
now under way and preparations are also going on to strike a deal
between the management and the new financial partner, Civil
Aviation and Tourism Minister Mosharraf Hossain said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"Forty percent of the shares will be sold to a reputed
international airline while the rest 9 percent will be sold to its
own employees," he said.
</P>
<P>
The World Bank has extended its support for finalizing this
process and agreed to provide 2 million U.S. dollars, said the
minister, who is also chairman of the board of directors of Biman.
</P>
<P>
Biman would also undergo overhauling in a bid to make it a
commercially profitable organization, he added.
</P>
<P>
At present, the Biman fleet includes four DC 10-30s, two
Airbuses, one F-28s and two ATPs. With an asset of 15.87 billion
taka (about 337.7 million dollars), Biman has a loan burden of
11.56 billion taka (about 267 million dollars). 
</P>
