<HEADLINE> Clinton to Meet Separately with Netanyahu, Arafat </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 24 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill
Clinton will meet separately with Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu and Palestinian President Yasser Arafat next week,
seeking to break the deadlock in the Middle East peace process.
</P>
<P>
In a brief statement, the White House said Thursday that
Clinton would meet Netanyahu at the White House on Monday morning
and would hold talks with Arafat later in the week.
</P>
<P>
U.S. officials played down expectations for the White House
meetings, saying no overall accord will emerge from the
discussions.
</P>
<P>
"We're at a point where the president's intervention can help
narrow the gaps," said a U.S. official.
</P>
<P>
"I don't expect a resolution of this next week. I think there
will be further work that we need to do."
</P>
<P>
The official told reporters at the White House that there were
no plans for a three-way meeting between Clinton, Netanyahu and
Arafat. "These are separate meetings. There are no plans for a
trilateral," he said.
</P>
<P>
At the United Nations headquarters in New York, U.S. Secretary
of State Madeleine Albright, who met Netanyahu on Wednesday, was
to meet the Israeli prime minister again and Arafat separately on
Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
Albright told reporters that the U.S. wanted concrete results
from its current diplomatic push, but she too was cautious about
predicting progress.
</P>
<P>
"We will try to lock in whatever we have agreed upon and I
can't predict that at this point because we are in the middle of
having these discussions," she said. 
</P>
