<HEADLINE> Albanian Ruling Party Agrees to Cabinet Reshuffle </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIRANA, September 24 (Xinhua) -- The Albanian ruling Socialist
Party gave Albanian Prime Minister Fatos Nano a vote of confidence
on Thursday and agreed to Cabinet changes after consultations with
four other parties in the ruling coalition.
</P>
<P>
The Cabinet reshuffle is the fifth since the government took
office in July 1997.
</P>
<P>
At a meeting of the party's Steering Council, Nano asked his
party members to approve the vote of confidence and reconfirmed
his premiership so that he could consult with other parties, the
president and the parliament about the reshuffle.
</P>
<P>
He insisted Cabinet changes be made within the coalition. He
said that to hold earlier general elections and make concessions
under pressure were harmful for the country and not the way to
establish a government.
</P>
<P>
Opposition parties are exerting pressure on the government and
demanding Nano and his cabinet resign.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister reaffirmed that his government would take a
series of measures to stablize public order and the economic
situation in Albania, to fight against corruption, and to approve
the new constitution on schedule.
</P>
<P>
Nano told reporters after the meeting that Cabinet changes
would be based on suggestions made by the European Union, the EU
Commission and the Organization for Security and Cooperation in
Europe.
</P>
<P>
The three organizations criticized the Albanian government
claiming that it was dilatory in implementing the administrative
program and did not forcefully crack down on organized crime,
smuggling and corruption. 
</P>
