<HEADLINE> India's Steel Industry Faces Difficulty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, September 25 (Xinhua) -- The Credit Rating
Information Services of India Ltd. (CRISIL) has predicted a bad
scenario in the short term for Indian steel manufacturers.
</P>
<P>
Influenced by lower prices in the Asian region, the current
fiscal 1998-99 would be another difficult year for the Indian
steel industry, CRISIL sources said here Friday.
</P>
<P>
CRISIL anticipates further weakening of Indian steel
manufacturers' credit quality during the current year. The Indian
steel scenario may be further impacted by the lackluster growth
rate in domestic consumption, significantly lower than anticipated
off-take from infrastructure projects and progressively eroding
cost competitiveness in the wake of the regional financial
climate.
</P>
<P>
The woes of the country's steel industry are worsened as a
result of hikes in the prices of petroleum products and railway
freight besides regular increase in power tariffs. Besides, the
debt level of the industry is fairly high in view of the pressures
on volumes and realizations, which could aggravate further.
Outstanding ratings in the industry would also come under
increased pressure.
</P>
<P>
The Indian steel companies on the one hand are facing
substantial anti-dumping duties on their products in the
international markets and on the other hand they are required to
compete with cheaper imports in the domestic market. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
