<DOCNO> XIE19980925.0201 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Wage Reform Revitalizing State-owned Firms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENYANG, September 25 (Xinhua) -- Major cities in northeast
China's Liaoning Province are reforming the existing wage system
of industrial firms in a bid to raise efficiency and bring all
money-losing enterprises out of red in three years.
</P>
<P>
Provincial statistics show that 25 key state-owned firms in six
major cities in Liaoning, which has a concentration of one-tenth
of China's large and medium-sized state enterprises, have been
chosen for a pilot program to install a yearly salary system,
which will link the earnings of managers, technicians and workers
to the performance of their firms.
</P>
<P>
Under the new wage system, the government signed contracts with
factory managers and provided them with high annual salaries
ranging from 21,200 to 126,847 yuan, eight or ten times that of a
worker's annual income.
</P>
<P>
Managers' salaries are now connected to the growth of
enterprise net assets, profits earned, and taxes paid to the
state.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, the income of technicians will be based on
the number and the quality of projects they have contracted, and
salesmens' salaries will be linked to their sales.
</P>
<P>
Vice Provincial Governor Chen Zhenggao said this is a
breakthrough in the distribution system at state-owned industrial
firms in China, though it is common practice at privately and
collectively owned businesses.
</P>
<P>
The aim of the reform is to tap the enormous potential of
managers and workers in state-owned enterprises and boost their
economic results, he added.
</P>
<P>
For decades, directors and workers of state-owned enterprises
all received their salaries regardless of profit or loss at their
work units.
</P>
<P>
Economic reform now grants greater power to factory directors
who bear the sole responsibility for their profits and
losses.
</P>
<P>
However, up to now, their salaries did not fluctuate in line
with the performance of their enterprises.
</P>
<P>
Chen said: "That practice hardly aroused the spontaneous
enthusiasm of managers and workers."
</P>
<P>
According to a recent survey conducted by the provincial
economic and trade commission, 14 of the 25 enterprises practicing
the new wage system raised their sales value by 13 percent last
year. Their pre-tax profits soared 17.1 percent and workers'
incomes also rose considerably.
</P>
<P>
Over 95 percent of enterprise managers and 67 percent of
workers approve of the new wage system.
</P>
<P>
A female worker at the Shenyang Aluminium Factory said: "I
don't care how much the director earns. So long as he runs the
factory well, we can all earn more too."
</P>
<P>
This reform will be spread to more cities in Liaoning and other
provinces in the near future.
</P>
<P>
Chen said two principles should be followed in reforming the
wage system: one is to concentrate on market demand and
efficiency, and the other is to make sure all occupations work out
measures suitable to their individual conditions.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980925.0202 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Colombian Guerrilla Group Proposes Prisoner Exchange </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANTAFE DE BOGOTA, September 24 (Xinhua) -- The Colombian
National Liberation Army (ELN) has proposed to the government an
exchange of 20 policemen they have held captive since September 12
with jailed guerrillas, the El Tiempo newspaper said on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The officers were seized in a guerrilla attack on the barracks
in the village of Las Mercedes in the northeast of the country.
ELN second-in-command Antonio Garcia said they were in good health.
</P>
<P>
"We are ready to negotiate an exchange for some of the hundreds
of political prisoners," Garcia was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
He said that the ELN, the second biggest guerrilla group in the
country, was ready to listen to government proposals about a
prisoner exchange -- the first such offer by the guerrilla
organization.
</P>
<P>
The country's largest guerrilla force -- the Revolutionary
Armed Forces of Colombia, which has captured more than 250
military personnel and policemen since last December, has insisted
on exchanging them with jailed guerrillas one by one.
</P>
<P>
The government established a special commission on Wednesday to
tackle the issue, the report said. 
