<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tokyo, Seoul Reach Basic Accord on Fisheries Pact </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, September 25 (Xinhua) -- Japan and South Korea reached a
basic accord early Friday morning on a new fisheries pact after
making concessions on disputed boundaries of a provisional fishing
zone and fishing catches, Kyodo News reported.
</P>
<P>
The basic agreement was reached at a meeting between Japanese
Prime Minister Keizo Obuchi, Agriculture, Forestry and Fisheries
Minister Shoichi Nakagawa and South Korean Maritime Affairs and
Fisheries Minister Kim Sun Gil, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, the two countries will draw a line between
their provisional fishing zones at a point halfway between the
lines they had insisted on.
</P>
<P>
Specifically, the two countries will establish the fishing zone
around a disputed group of islets in the Sea of Japan, called
Takeshima in Japan and Tokto in South Korea, 35 nautical miles
from the shores of the two countries, with a demarcation line at
135 degrees 30 minutes east, government sources said.
</P>
<P>
The delineation of the provisional fishing zone, where the two
countries will jointly control fishing operations, has been one of
the most contentious issues surrounding the pact because Tokyo and
Seoul have long been at odds over ownership of the disputed islets.
</P>
<P>
The two countries also agreed to limit their fishing catches in
each other's economic waters to the same specified amount in three
to five years.
</P>
<P>
In recent years, Japan and South Korea have sought to conclude
a new fisheries pact in line with a U.N. convention allowing
countries to set 200-nautical-mile exclusive economic zones around
their shores.
</P>
<P>
But negotiations between them collapsed in January after Japan
terminated a bilateral 1965 fisheries pact. The talks resumed in
April.
</P>
<P>
The two countries have expressed their intentions to conclude a
new fisheries pact before South Korean President Kim Dae Jung
arrives in Tokyo on October 7 for a four-day visit. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980925.0205 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-25 </DATE_TIME>
