<HEADLINE> Myanmar, Singapore to Discuss Economic Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, September 25 (Xinhua) -- A Myanmar-Singapore Joint
Ministerial Working Committee (JMWC) will meet in Yangon later
this year for the third time to promote the two countries'
economic cooperation, trade and investment.
</P>
<P>
Singapore has been rendering assistance to Myanmar for the
development of its hotel and tourism industry, agricultural
production, livestock and fisheries, human resources development,
commerce, transport, communications and science and technology.
</P>
<P>
The JMWC was formed after an agreement on bilateral economic
cooperation was concluded when Chairman of the Myanmar State Peace
 and Development Council Senior General Than Shwe visited
Singapore in June 1995.
</P>
<P>
According to official statistics, Singapore's investment in
Myanmar amounted to 1.35 billion U.S. dollars in 66 projects at
the end of June this year, ranking first among 23 countries and
regions which have a total investment of 6.8 billion dollars in
the country.
</P>
<P>
The statistics also show that the two countries' bilateral
trade stood at 833.7 million dollars in the 1997-98 fiscal year
which ended in March, up from 633 million dollars in the previous
year.
</P>
<P>
Singapore exported to Myanmar 716.5 million dollars worth of
goods, while importing 117.2 million dollars of commodities from
Myanmar during the period. 
</P>
</TEXT>
