<HEADLINE> Bulgaria, India to Cooperate in Various Fields </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SOFIA, September 24 (Xinhua) -- Bulgaria and India signed a
trade agreement here on Thursday that would foster a new range of
food products and reinvigorate Bulgaria's struggling industrial
sector.
</P>
<P>
The protocol of cooperation between the two countries would
also allow Indian companies to invest in Bulgaria and take
advantage of its duty-free access to the markets of the European
Union.
</P>
<P>
The agreement would help Indian firms to take advantage of the
Central European Free Trade Association, covering Poland, the
Czech Republic, Slovakia, Hungary, Slovenia, Romania and Bulgaria,
and the European Free Trade Association, which includes Iceland,
Norway, Switzerland and Liechtenstein.
</P>
<P>
The one-year agreement, covering agriculture, industry, energy
production and transport, was signed by Indian State Minister for
Agriculture Som Pal and Bulgarian Trade and Tourism Minister
Valentin Vasilev on Thursday at the 12th session of the Mixed
Committee for Economic and Scientific-Technical Cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Indian businesses have shown an interest in Bulgaria's
sunflower seed production with intention of exporting the oil to
India, while other Indian companies are ready to take part in the
rehabilitation of the Varna thermal power station and upgrade
Bulgarian railways, Pal said.
</P>
<P>
Bulgarian-Indian joint ventures will manufacture yogurt and
wine with Bulgarian technology. Cooperation is also possible in
fruit, vegetable and meat processing, Pal said.
</P>
<P>
Trade between the two countries in the first seven months of
this year added up to 10.4 million US dollars, according to Indian
figures.
</P>
<P>
Bulgaria imported goods worth 8.49 million dollars and its
exports there were 1.87 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
Last year, Bulgaria's imports were a little over seven million
dollars and exports were 17.7 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
Talks were also held on drafting an agreement for mutual
protection and encouragement of investments to complete the legal
framework of economic cooperation, Vasilev said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
