<DOCNO> XIE19980925.0209 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Italian Prime Minister on Debt, Deficit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, September 24 (Xinhua) -- Italian Prime Minister Romano
Prodi said Thursday that Italy has no alternative to cutting the
pubic debt from 118 percent of gross domestic product (GDP) to 100
percent within six years and curbing budget deficits to 1.2
percent of GDP.
</P>
<P>
As a government spokesman affirmed that a political crisis
would jeopardize a promise of tax rebates at the end of the year,
Prodi said the deficit and debt goals "are absolutely binding on
our country and thus represent a limit and a condition placed on
our public financing choices".
</P>
<P>
With the cabinet preparing to make the 1999 budget bill public
on Friday, the prospect that the ruling center-left coalition
could stumble and fall loomed larger after Prodi failed to win
Communist Refoundation Party backing for the bill, essential for
passing it into law in the Lower House.
</P>
<P>
In his statement on Thursday, the prime minister seemed to be
addressing the Communist Refoundation Party's demands for
expanding spending to combat unemployment and bolster benefits for
the poor and other less-privileged groups.
</P>
<P>
He said European economic and monetary union required all
member states to look closely at their resources and find the best
way to dovetail public accounts and commitments to the European
Union.
</P>
<P>
At a meeting of municipal, provincial and regional
representatives, Prodi promised government efforts to ease
indebtedness at these levels and reiterated his intention to apply
a "sharp and very precise choice" in pursuing the reform of the
pubic sector.
</P>
<P>
On the road to European economic and monetary union Italy has
embarked on, Prodi said: "We knew we would have to remain loyal to
difficult pacts and respect very incisive parameters. And we knew
from the beginning that to do this wee needed the cooperation of
the entire country ... and of our complex system of local
governments."
</P>
<P>
Prodi went on to say that his government was not aiming at
development dictated from the top but at "flexible development
capable of being adapted to different conditions and to the
exploitation of all potentialities".
</P>
<P>
This development, he continued, needed cooperation at all
levels and the help of the trade unions and business and industry
organizations as well.
</P>
<P>
On Prodi's remarks on the public debt and budget deficits, a
communique issued by his office pointed out that the government's
three-year economic and financial guidelines had set the goal of a
deficit-GDP ratio of two percent for 1999, compared to 2.6 percent
for the present year.
</P>
<P>
The guidelines also chart a course for reducing the public debt
as a percentage of GDP per year from 1998 to 2001.
</P>
<P>
Also on Thursday, the prime minister's spokesman, Ricardo
Franco Levi said plans for returning to taxpayers 60 percent of
the once-off euro-tax levied last year would be endangered by a
government crisis.
</P>
<P>
Levi said the problem of adding the rebate to December wage
packets was "very simple" in that if the government falls and the
budget is not passed into law, "the provisional administration
cannot contain any of the measures written into the budget".
</P>
<P>
"So there would be no coverage for repaying the euro-tax or
even for the measures on unemployment and the less-privileged
sector," he added.
</P>
<P>
The budget bill sets aside three trillion lire (1.76 billion
U.S. dollars) for reimbursing 60 percent of the special tax
applied to ensure that Italy's 1997 deficit as a ratio of GDP
would qualify the country for entry to the European single
currency this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
