<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Implement New Land-Use Law </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 25 (Xinhua) -- China will institute the
strictest measures in the world to regulate land use and protect
arable land through the implementation of a new land-use law, in
an effort to ensure sustainable economic and social development.
</P>
<P>
The new law will officially go into effect on January 1, 1999,
Zhou Yongkang, minister of Land and Natural Resources, announced
this morning at a press conference hosted by the Information
Office of the State Council.
</P>
<P>
Each province, autonomous region, and municipality should make
efforts to ensure that the amount of arable land under its
jurisdiction does not decrease. Farmland under special protection
should account for more than 80 percent of the total, according to
the law.
</P>
<P>
China is rich in land resources, but weak in per capital
availability of land resources, especially arable land
resources. The country has 22 percent of the world's population,
but less than ten percent of the world's arable land.
</P>
<P>
According to the new law, land is divided into farmland, land
for construction, and unutilized land, and land use should be in
line with its proper category.
</P>
<P>
Land for construction should be under strict control, and
compensation for land acquisition will be raised, the law says.
</P>
<P>
The right to approve land use will be given back to the central
and provincial governments, according to the new law.
</P>
<P>
The new land-use law also strengthens law-enforcement
supervision and calls for deepened land-use reform.
</P>
<P>
Zhou said the new land-use law is an overall adjustment of the
existing one, not just a few amendments to the articles, and
signals a major transfer in the use and management of land.
</P>
<P>
The existing Land-Use Law, which took effect a decade ago, has
played its role in developing and utilizing land resources and
protecting arable land, but it cannot resolve the knotty problems
which have appeared on the way to a socialist market economy, he
said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980925.0215 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-25 </DATE_TIME>
