<HEADLINE> Employment Improves in Mexico </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, September 24 (Xinhua) -- Employment in Mexico
improved significantly in the first eight months this year,
reflecting an overall economic growth in the country, Finance
Minister Jose Angel Gurria told the Senate on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Gurria said the number of workers affiliated with the Mexican
Institute of Social Security (IMSS) increased by 643,000 in the
January-August period, more than one third of which were permanent
workers.
</P>
<P>
A total of 10,095,566 workers have so far been registered at
the IMSS, he added.
</P>
<P>
Savings have also witnessed a recovery, going from 14.8 percent
of the gross domestic product (GDP) in 1994 to some 25 percent at
present, while the gross fixed investment increased by 16.8
percent in the last six months.
</P>
<P>
The minister said Mexico has a manageable current account
deficit, a schedule for servicing foreign debt and a flexible rate
of exchange, allowing the country to bear external financial
impacts without the risk of depleting its international reserves
or altering the rate of exchange. 
</P>
