<HEADLINE> Guangdong Adopts Industrial Injury Insurance Law </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, September 25 (Xinhua) -- South China's Guangdong
Province has passed regulations on industrial injuries insurance
which will become effective in November.
</P>
<P>
The regulations include concrete stipulations on the scope of
insurance and evaluations of the extent of workers' injuries.
</P>
<P>
The insurance scope covers ten types of industrial injuries
including drivers injured in traffic accidents during working
hours, workers who are disabled or killed on the job, employees
hurt in traffic accidents going to or coming from work, and
workers disabled by occupational diseases.
</P>
<P>
The regulations stipulate that the amount of pensions or
compensation for the families of deceased workers will be
determined according to wage scales.
</P>
<P>
The regulations warns that workers or their relatives can be
severely fined for making false claims.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980925.0220 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ADB Loan For Sri Lanka's Urban Development </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, September 25 (Xinhua) -- The Asian Development Bank
(ADB) has approved a loan of 70 million U.S. dollars for Sri Lanka
to improve urban infrastructure and finance housing improvement
for low income households, the ADB office here said Friday.
</P>
<P>
The project will also give local authorities more
responsibility for providing and financing infrastructure and
municipal services.
</P>
<P>
Deficiencies in basic infrastructure has restrained urban areas
from playing a more active role in the economy's growth, the ADB
noted in a release noted.
</P>
<P>
Most secondary towns have piped water supply but up to 40
percent of water is lost through poor construction and lack of
maintenance. Inadequate drainage systems lead to flooding during
the monsoon. Roads are of poor quality and ill-maintained.
</P>
<P>
The total cost of the project is 100 million dollars. The ADB
loan will come from its Special Funds resources, which are
interest-free and repayable over 40 years.
</P>
<P>
The project will improve roads, water supply and drainage
systems, bus terminals and public markets in 27 secondary towns in
Sri Lanka.
</P>
<P>
Another part of the project will support efforts between local
authorities and private land owners to develop unplanned and
unserviced urban land, the release said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
