<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S., Panama Disagree on U.S. Military Presense in Panama </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 24 (Xinhua) -- The United States and
Panama announced Thursday night that they failed to reach an
agreement on permitting American troops to remain in Panama beyond
the end of the century.
</P>
<P>
"Despite extensive efforts by both countries, and many areas of
common interest, an accord on the establishment of a MCC
(multinational counter-narcotics center) in Panama was not
attainable," the two countries said in a joint statement.
</P>
<P>
The announcement means that for the first time since 1903, when
Panama became independent with help from the U.S., no U.S. troops
will be based in Panama.
</P>
<P>
The Panama Canal treaties require the departure of American
soldiers by December 31, 1999, when control over the waterway
reverts to Panama.
</P>
<P>
Since 1997, the two countries have sought agreement on
establishing the MCC in which military personnel from the U.S. and
many hemispheric countries would take part.
</P>
<P>
The counter-narcotics center would permit the U.S. to continue
anti-drug operations close to the major sources of cocaine
trafficking.
</P>
<P>
The negotiations failed because the U.S. Defense Department
insisted that American troops be allowed to carry out a range of
activities outside the framework of the counter-narcotics center,
including search and rescue operations, training flights,
humanitarian relief and logistical support activities.
</P>
<P>
U.S. officials argued it would not have been cost-effective for
the U.S. to maintain the anti-drug center if it were barred from
carrying out these functions.
</P>
<P>
The Panamanians, however, said that such activities would give
the appearance of an American military base in disguise. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980925.0224 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-25 </DATE_TIME>
