<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Feminists Urge Congress to Stop Efforts to Impeach Clinton </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 24 (Xinhua) -- Feminist leaders in the
United States Thursday called on the nation's women to demand that
the Republican-controlled Congress drop efforts to impeach
President Bill Clinton.
</P>
<P>
"Some of those leading the charge against Clinton are among the
worst foes of women's rights," a joint statement from several
organizations said. "The opponents of the president have a
political agenda that will harm women long after the scandal has
faded from the front pages."
</P>
<P>
"Women should write, call, telefax, e-mail, shout and tell
Congress, `Do not impeach this president and don't force him to
resign,'" said Yvonne Scruggs-Leftwich, head of the Black
Leadership Forum Inc.
</P>
<P>
Among others making similar demands were feminist pioneer Betty
Friedan; Patricia Ireland, president of the National Organization
for Women; and Eleanor Smeal, president of the Feminist Majority.
</P>
<P>
They said the accusations against the president do not rise to
the level of impeachable offenses.
</P>
<P>
At a news conference, Ireland said that Republicans "are mired
in a partisan game of chicken" and "seem determined not to stop
until this government crashes."
</P>
<P>
Smeal, while asserting that all women believe Clinton has much
to answer for in his admitted sexual relationship with Monica
Lewinsky, said that even if he lied about that relationship, he
did not commit an impeachable offense.
</P>
<P>
"We deplore his misconduct but we also understand the hypocrisy
of his opponents," she said. "We have years of progress at stake
if the president is hounded out of office. But worse yet, we risk
the ushering into power of a puritanical or fundamentalist sex
police which speaks of freedom but allows government to destroy
the rights of privacy."
</P>
<P>
But the feminists' position drew a quick negative reaction from
Carmen Pate, head of Concerned Women for America, a conservative
public policy group, which is meeting this weekend in Alexandria,
Virginia.
</P>
<P>
"We wholeheartedly disagree with them," she said. "We believe
the choices the president has made deserve consequences. We
believe he is guilty of perjury and obstruction of justice. At
this point, we just need to concentrate on removing the president
from office."
</P>
<P>
Polls taken in recent days show women remain slightly more
inclined than men to support Clinton, and women are less likely
than men to support impeachment if it were proved the president
lied under oath. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
