<HEADLINE> May Riots Instigated by Groups: Jakarta Officer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, September 25 (Xinhua) -- Jakarta Military Command
chief of staff Sudi Silalahi Thursday confirmed that the May riots
were apparently instigated by groups of people in an organized
manner but did not identify the mastermind, the Jakarta Post
reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
Sudi was questioned by the government-sponsored Joint
Fact-Finding Team investigating the riots on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Sudi was the seventh active or former government official the
team had examined.
</P>
<P>
Bambang W. Suharto, one of the team's members, told reporters
that the team believed that an organized group had provoked the
May riots in Jakarta.
</P>
<P>
He quoted Sudi and police sources as saying security
authorities are searching for the provocateurs' whereabouts and
dealing with some of them.
</P>
<P>
He said he is waiting for the result of the investigation into
the organized group.
</P>
<P>
The government established the Joint Fact-Finding Team in July
to investigate reports that the May 13-15 riots were masterminded.
More than 1,200 people were killed and thousands of buildings and
vehicles damaged during the riots in Jakarta and other cities.
</P>
<P>
Activists have said 168 women and children were raped or
sexually assaulted during the riots and 20 of whom died or
committed suicide.
</P>
<P>
Easter Indahyani Jusuf Lubis, chairwoman of Solidaritas Nusa
Bangsa, a non-governmental organization, claimed on Thursday that
it had hard evidence that sexual assaults and rapes did occur
during the riots.
</P>
<P>
She told a seminar that the organization had met with a doctor
who treated seven victims of sexual assaults during the riots. The
doctor had secured their medical records, including pictures of
mutilated genitals.
</P>
<P>
A source close to the organization told the Jakarta Post that
it intended to report the evidence to the rights body on Monday.
</P>
</TEXT>
