<HEADLINE> China's Cities Speed Up Road Construction </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 25 (Xinhua) -- The cities of Beijing and
Tianjin will undertake massive highway building projects to
alleviate growing traffic jams and keep pace with rapid economic
development.
</P>
<P>
Beijing, China's capital, will spend 20 billion yuan (about 2.4
billion US dollars) to build 1,236 kilometers of new roads over
the next five years to raise the city's highway density to 0.87
kilometers per square kilometer.
</P>
<P>
Most of this money will be used to build 10 key projects
including an expressway between Beijing and Shenyang, capital of
northeast China's Liaoning Province.
</P>
<P>
Other projects include three ring-roads connecting the capital
with 10 satellite cities and an expressway linking Beijing with
Kaifeng in central China's Henan Province.
</P>
<P>
By the end of 1997, Beijing had 12,209 kilometers of highway,
the most in China. The city plans to bring the highway network to
13,542 kilometers by the year 2002.
</P>
<P>
Tianjin plans to invest 10 billion yuan over the next four
years to build 476 kilometers of expressways and 320 kilometers of
highways, which will make it possible to raise the speed limit to
100 kilometers per hour.
</P>
<P>
A 43-kilometer-long expressway between Tangshan and Tianjin is
expected to open to traffic by the end of the year, and three more
roads will be completed next year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
