<HEADLINE> Indonesian Armed Forces Asked to Secure Reform </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, September 25 (Xinhua) -- Indonesian President B.J.
Habibie Thursday ordered all members of the Armed Forces (ABRI) to
secure the political reform agenda, national newspapers reported
Friday.
</P>
<P>
"I issue this instruction because there have been signs lately
of certain quarters who are not willing to see the reform agenda
to be implemented smoothly," the president said at a commander's
call ceremony here.
</P>
<P>
He accused certain groups, which he did not identify, of using
all possible means to foil the government's reform agenda,
including the general election and presidential election planned
respectively for May and December next year.
</P>
<P>
"Our campaign for reform is being marred by political actions
and activities which tend to put forward physical strength by
mobilizing crowds, either through demonstrations or other
activities which obstruct norms, rules and ethics," he said.
</P>
<P>
Students in Jakarta and other cities held rallies almost every
day this month to protest the spiraling prices for basic
commodities and urged President Habibie to take concrete measures
to solve the economic problems.
</P>
<P>
The president charged that the current wave of street protests
and demonstrations had gone too far and breached the limits of
tolerance.
</P>
<P>
"The looting and destruction done by irresponsible groups still
continue in several regions and are the factors that have slowed
economic recovery," he said.
</P>
<P>
"I ask all ranks of ABRI to act firmly against the looters and
rioters in accordance with standing procedures," he said.
</P>
<P>
Thursday's ceremony was the second meeting between the
president, who is the ABRI supreme commander, and the country's
top generals. The first meeting was held in June.
</P>
<P>
In a press release after the meeting, Wiranto appealed to all
parties to exercise self-restraint and stop any destructive act,
propaganda and instigation detrimental to the country's union and
cohesion.
</P>
<P>
The Armed Forces had come to a definite conclusion that all
forms of destructive action threatening peace and order as well as
the country's safety must be sternly dealt with, regardless of the
risks the country might face, he added. 
</P>
