<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Investment In Infrastructure Increased In Southern Chinese City </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAIKOU, September 25 (Xinhua) -- Haikou, capital of China's
island province of Hainan, has been spending 1.3 billion yuan
(about 157 million U.S. Dollars) on nine infrastructure projects
in urban areas since the beginning of the year.
</P>
<P>
Work on a 667-million-yuan sea bridge began in April. The
2,663-meter bridge is expected to open to traffic in 2001, helping
relieve pressure from traffic jams in urban areas. The bridge is
being built with the help of 50 million U.S. Dollars in Japanese
loans.
</P>
<P>
Nearly 200 million yuan will be used for a 6.5-kilometer dike
to control flooding on a river that runs into the sea from the
east of Haikou.
</P>
<P>
An estimated 220 million yuan will be spent on a 3.1-kilometer
tidal barrage along the sea.
</P>
<P>
A 340-million-yuan sewage treatment plant is expected to be
built in June next year, with a daily handling capacity of 300,000
tons of waste water, putting Haikou in the lead in China in
disposing of waste water.
</P>
<P>
The second phase of construction work on waterworks is due to
be completed at the end of this year, supplying 240,000 tons of
water a day and mostly meeting the water supply demand in urban
areas.
</P>
<P>
Work is also going on for the improvement of the city's
electric power grid and transport network with state loans.
</P>
</TEXT>
