<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NATO to Issue Ultimatum to Yugoslavia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LISBON, September 24 (Xinhua) -- The North Atlantic Council
approved the decision on Thursday to issue an ultimatum to
Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic, demanding an end of attacks
on civilians in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
"Today's decision is an important political signal of NATO's
readiness to use force if it becomes necessary," NATO Secretary
General Javier Solana said.
</P>
<P>
Solana also expressed NATO's "strong support" to a
U.N. resolution demanding an end to violence in the Serbian
province of Kosovo and threatening further action if fighting
continues. The U.N. Security Council passed the Kosovo resolution
on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The NATO chief was in the southern Portuguese resort town of
Vilamoura to attend a two-day informal meeting of NATO defense
ministers.
</P>
<P>
The NATO defense ministers met after the North Atlantic Council
decided to request an air force for possible action in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
The 16-nation alliance issued an "activation warning,"saying
air forces would be required for "both the limited air option and
a phased air campaign in Kosovo."
</P>
<P>
For the first time, Poland, the Czech Republic and Hungary --
the three nations due to join NATO in April -- were invited to
participate in the NATO meeting. They promised to coordinate their
actions with NATO members on the Kosovo crisis. 
</P>
</TEXT>
