<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Flood-Ravaged Parts of China Trying To Meet Economic Goals </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LANZHOU, September 25 (Xinhua) -- Parts of China that were hit
by the serious flooding this year are trying to meet their
economic growth targets in spite of the heavy losses they have
suffered.
</P>
<P>
Planning officials from Hubei, Hunan, Jiangxi and Jilin
provinces as well as the Inner Mongolia Autonomous Region attended
a meeting here and agreed that large scale infrastructure
investment supported by the central and local governments is the
key to guaranteeing this. Infrastructure spending will not only go
as planned, but be increased.
</P>
<P>
The performance of these regions is said to be crucial to
meeting this year's national economic target of 8-percent growth,
analysts say.
</P>
<P>
The economy of Hubei is expected to grow by 12 percent, Hunan
by 10 percent, Jiangxi by 11 percent, Jilin by 9 percent, and
Inner Mongolia by 10 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
