<HEADLINE> Two Rookies Represent U.S. in Davis Cup Semifinal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 24 (Xinhua) -- U.S. is relying heavily
on two rookies to match an experienced Italian team in this
weekend's Davis Cup semifinal at the Milwaukee Arena.
</P>
<P>
Captain Tom Gullikson fielded veteran Todd Martin, who will
play both singles and doubles, with the back-up by two
21-year-old Jan-Michael Gambill and Justin Gimelstob as former
world number one Jim Courier, who recently ranked 70, still sits
on the sidelines.
</P>
<P>
World No. 50 Gambill makes his Davis Cup debut against
37th-ranked Andrea Gaudenzi in Friday's first match while the
28th-ranked Martin takes on 47th-ranked Davide Sanguinetti.
Martin has a 10-2 winning record in Davis Cup singles.
</P>
<P>
Martin and Gimelstob will face Gaudenzi and Diego Nargiso in
saturday's doubles match.
</P>
<P>
The reverse singles on Sunday features Martin against
Gaudenzi, followed by Gambill and Sanguinetti.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. met Italy nine times in Davis Cup and the U.S. leads
7-2.
</P>
<P>
Gambill, who started the year with a ranking of 176, admitted
to being surprised he was selected over Courier for action.
</P>
<P>
"This is a great opportunity for all of us," Martin said.
</P>
<P>
With both teams agreeing that the indoor surface is playing
slow, the Italians are feeling a little more comfortable about
their chances. 
</P>
</TEXT>
