<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 01:00 GMT, September 25 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS -- U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan on Thursday
welcomed India's willingness to conclude the discussion on signing
the Comprehensive Nuclear-Test-Ban Treaty (CTBT).
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the 53rd Session of the General Assembly, Indian
Prime Minister Atal Bihari Vajpayee announced that India was
prepared to sign CTBT within one year. (Annan-India-Nuclear)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- U.S. President Bill Clinton Thursday welcomed
Pakistan's offer to sign a nuclear test ban treaty and urged the
U.S. Senate to ratify it.
</P>
<P>
"We're very pleased by the statement that the government of
Pakistan has now made with respect to the Comprehensive Test Ban
Treaty," White House spokesman Mike McCurry
said. (US-Pakistan-Nuclear)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
LONDON -- Author Salman Rushdie on Thursday reacted with relief
to the news that Iran has dropped its support for a bounty to be
paid for his assassination.
</P>
<P>
"Well, it looks like it is over," Rushdie told Sky Television
outside the Foreign Office after a briefing from government
minister Derek Fatchett. (Iran-Rushdie)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- The Judiciary Committee of the U.S. House of
Representatives announced on Thursday it will vote on October 5 or
6 whether to launch a formal impeachment inquiry into charges
against President Bill Clinton.
</P>
<P>
Chairman Henry Hyde, a Republican, said if the committee
approved the inquiry, the full House would vote on the measure,
probably on October 8 or 9. (US-Clinton-Scandal)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
MAPUTO -- Mozambican President Joaquim Chissano said here
Thursday that the decision of the Southern African Development
Community (SADC) to send troops to Lesotho was aimed at restoring
peace in the country.
</P>
<P>
Chissano told reporters at the State House that there was no
alternative. He denied the claim that Mozambique's stance on
Lesotho issue goes against that on the Congo
crisis. (Mozambique-Lesotho)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS -- The unilateral declaration of a Palestinian
state would cause the collapse of the Middle East peace process,
Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu said here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu was responding to the repeated statement by
Palestinian leaders that they would proclaim an independent state
if a final peace agreement with Israel was not concluded by next
May. (UN-Israel-Palestinians)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS -- The U.N. Security Council Thursday convened
the second ministerial Meeting on Africa to gather more
international efforts to bring peace, stability and development to
the conflict-torn Africa.
</P>
<P>
Foreign ministers from the 15 Security Council member states,
including Chinese Foreign Minister Tang Jiaxuan, were present at
the meeting, which was held on the sidelines of the 53rd General
Assembly session. (UN-Security Council-Africa)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- U.S. President Bill Clinton was told by Russian
Foreign Minister Igor Ivanov during a meeting Thursday that Russia
opposes the use of force to end the violence in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
Following their meeting at the White House, Ivanov told
reporters that his country opposes military strikes to end the
bloodshed in the Yugoslav province. (US-Russia-Kosovo)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY -- Expelled Afghan Taliban Charge D'affaires to
Saudi Arabia Mawlawi Shehab Eddine Dalawer left Riyadh Thursday
for home, with the Taliban's embassy still working, the Kuwait
News Agency (Kuna) reported.
</P>
<P>
This was confirmed by Abdelwahab Moulawi Said, first secretary
at the Taliban's embassy in Riyadh, during a telephone interview
with Kuna. (Saudi Arabia-Taliban-Relations)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
ATHENS -- Greece once again urged Thursday the international
community to find a political solution to the Kosovo problem,
saying that Athens was doubtful about the effectiveness of a
military intervention.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference, Greek government spokesman
Dimitris Reppas said that Greece continued to have reservations
about the possibility of a strike by international forces on
Kosovo and would continue to urge a political resolution to the
problem. (Greece-Kosovo)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG -- Lesotho King Letsie III was Thursday barred by
the government from speaking to his nation through
state-controlled Radio Lesotho.
</P>
<P>
The country's Information and Broadcasting Minister Mnyani
Mphafi told local radio reporters that whatever was to go on air,
including the king's message, had to be approved by the
government, in particular, by Prime Minister Pakalitha Mosisili,
South African Press Association (SAPA) reported. (Lesotho-King)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
TOKYO -- Japan should look at history in a right perspective
and handle the Taiwan issue properly, Zhang Wannian, Vice Chairman
of the Central Military Commission of China, told Japanese defense
officials Thursday.
</P>
<P>
In a meeting with Director-General of Japan's Defense Agency
Fukushiro Nukaga, Zhang said Sino-Japanese relations are generally
good despite the ups and downs since the two countries normalized
their diplomatic ties 20 years ago. (Japan-China-Visit) 
</P>
