<DOCNO> XIE19980925.0252 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> FA Moves to Stamp out Sleaze </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 24 (Xinhua) -- The Football Association is
to appoint a trouble-shooter with wide-ranging powers to stamp
out sleaze within the English game.
</P>
<P>
The initiative is intended to crack down on the sort of
scandals which have dogged soccer over the past few years on and
off the field.
</P>
<P>
One of the most important areas for investigation will be club
finances, because of the hundreds of millions of pounds which
have poured into the national game since the birth of live
televised football.
</P>
<P>
The moves follow the recommendations of former Metropolitan
Police deputy commissioner Sir John Smith in his report into
football's finances and reputation in January.
</P>
<P>
The announcement came within hours of a soccer scout being
ordered to pay a total of 10,000 pounds by the FA following the
so-called 'bungs inquiry'.
</P>
<P>
Former Arsenal chief scout Steve Burtenshaw, now chief scout
at QPR, admitted misconduct last week at a hearing before an FA
commission in connection with the transfer of midfielder John J
ensen from Danish club Brondby to Arsenal in 1992.
</P>
<P>
He apologised at the hearing for having accepted 35,000 pounds
from agent Rune Hauge two months after Jensen arrived at Highbury
in the transfer deal which led to former Arsenal boss George
Graham's one-year ban from the game.
</P>
<P>
His legal team is considering an appeal, believing the fine of
7,500 and order to pay 2,500 costs are unduly severe.
</P>
<P>
The FA said it had already written to the Government making it
clear it endorsed Sir John's recommendations in principle, and
was committed to introduce them backed by the necessary financial
resources.
</P>
<P>
"Several hundred applicants are already being considered for a
new senior post to deal specifically with all disciplinary issues
which often require detailed investigation and prosecution," said
a Football Association spokesman.
</P>
<P>
"The successful candidate's task will cover offences as varied
as violent conduct, financial irregularities and racist abuse.
</P>
<P>
"Meanwhile, the FA's new finance director is developing
specific proposals in consultation with the clubs that may lead
to the creation of a financial advisory department. This will
assist and advise clubs on financial matters," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
