<HEADLINE> Graham Refuses to be Drawn into Spurs Speculation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 24 (Xinhua) -- Tottenham Hotspur said on
Thursday that Leeds United's George Graham had yet to agree to
become their new coach.
</P>
<P>
Graham himself refused to be drawn into the intense
speculation linking him with the vacant job at White Hart Lane
but many Leeds fans are resigned to losing him.
</P>
<P>
Tottenham, who play Leeds in the premier league at White Hart
Lane on Saturday, said in a statement: "It is true discussions
have been going on between the clubs but there is no truth in
reports he has already agreed to take charge."
</P>
<P>
Graham, 54, told Leeds United's Clubcall: "I am the manager of
Leeds United and we are going to Tottenham on Saturday looking
for three points. The rest is just a side issue."
</P>
<P>
Ray Fell, chairman of the Leeds Supporters' Club, said the
feeling among the fans was that "George was on his way".
</P>
<P>
"Fans are getting fed up with contracts meaning nothing in
football. It seems the only people with any loyalty are the fans."
</P>
<P>
Graham, a former player and manager of Tottenham's arch-rivals
Arsenal, would not, initially at least, be a popular choice among
Spurs fans.
</P>
<P>
The club have been without a manager since Christian Gross was
sacked on September 5.
</P>
<P>
Former manager David Pleat has been put in temporary charge of
the team who have won three, drawn one and lost one of the five
league and cup matches under his control. 
