<DOCNO> XIE19980925.0256 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Balanced Development Urged in Globalization  (by Gu Zhenqiu) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 24 (Xinhua) -- Developing countries
from Africa, Asia and Latin America called for a balance of
development between North and South in the globalization process,
which is mainly characterized by strengthened interdependence
among members of the global family.
</P>
<P>
In their speeches to the general debate of the 53rd General
Assembly session, which entered the fourth day on Thursday,
leaders from the developing world voiced their concerns over the
negative effects brought about by globalization.
</P>
<P>
It is their consensus, though produced in a separate manner,
that no country can stand alone in today's world, and no nation
can be immune to the suffering of other nations. Developing
countries are especially in poorer position to greet the process
of globalization due to the existing unfair international
political and economic order.
</P>
<P>
The pros and cons of economic globalization has been better
perceived following the July 1997 outbreak of the financial crisis
in Southeast Asia.
</P>
<P>
Ripples have spread widely in the world from the economic
upheavals of Southeast Asia and Russia, and nearly every corner of
the global village has been affected, but only varying in degrees,
they said. Put starkly, the financial crisis threatened emerging
economies from Latin America to South Africa.
</P>
<P>
Leonardo Santos Simao, foreign minister of Mozambique, said,
"The crisis which initially began as an isolated case in the Asian
economies has rapidly spread to virtually all continents. Its
consequences have demonstrated that no country in this globalized
economy is immune to the suffering of other nations."
</P>
<P>
"We cannot afford to leave vast segments of nations and peoples
unattended and still confronted with basic challenges, such as
famine, epidemic diseases, inadequate water distribution, among
others," he added.
</P>
<P>
His remarks were echoed by South African President Nelson
Mandela, who said that the eradication of poverty remains one of
the major tasks in the developing world under the current unfair
international economic order.
</P>
<P>
"We have a situation in which the further accumulation of
wealth, rather than contribution to the improvement of the quality
of life of all humanity, is generating poverty at a frightening
accelerated pace," he said.
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, Bangladesh also reaches the same conclusion.
Foreign Minister Abdus Azad told the General Assembly that "the
process of globalization, and liberalization bring risks, grave
challenges as well as opportunities -- but in unequal ways."
</P>
<P>
"The external economic shocks associated with this process are
too powerful for the vulnerable economies to absorb," he said,
"This has now being recognized even by beneficiaries of
globalization."
</P>
<P>
Far away from Bangladesh, Venezuela also approaches to the
process of globalization from the same perspective. Delivering his
speech at the General Assembly, President Rafael Caldera said,
"This complex phenomenon that we have come to call globalization,
in addition to its positive aspects and the progress it entails,
can also have progressively negative effects for the emerging
developing countries."
</P>
<P>
An integral component of the globalization process, which takes
shape on the basis of technical advancement and rapid flow of
information, is unfettered movement of the factors of production,
including capital and labor.
</P>
<P>
Better perception of the problem, to a large extent, paves the
way for effective and workable solutions. The developing countries
not only raised questions at the U.N. forum, but also put forward
some proposals to solve the problems in the economic and financial
field.
</P>
<P>
A careful study can find that their proposals have one thing in
common. That is, they all cry out to have concerted international
efforts in seeking the relevant solutions.
</P>
<P>
"We need to formulate a positive and workable agenda for
ensuring that the globalization process promotes equality and
benefit for all," Azad said.
</P>
<P>
"The maladies that spring from economic globalization requires
remedies which are global in scope, remedies which must take
account of the ailments of all States, and not be based solely on
the prescriptions advanced by those who may seem to be secure,"
said the president of Sri Lanka, Chandrika Kumaratunga, in her
speech.
</P>
<P>
Currently, the developing countries, the least developed
countries in particular, are undertaking an uphill task to help
themselves out of pains in the wake of the globalization process.
</P>
<P>
But for one thing to be sure, the United Nations can also play
a role in coordinating global efforts to expand world economy
while keeping off negative effects of globalization.
</P>
<P>
U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan has a more profound
conception. "Globalization will depend on the balance between rich
and poor, on the more advanced nations, the intermediately
advanced nations, and the least advanced nations, on the
application of equitable formulas to alleviate 'the external debt
burden'."  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980925.0257 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-25 </DATE_TIME>
