<HEADLINE> 2002 Winter Olympics Gets 1.4 Billion Budget </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 24 (Xinhua) -- The organizing committee
of the 2002 Winter Olympics raised a proposed 1.4 billion US
dollars budget for the Games on Thursday at Salt Lake City, the
United States.
</P>
<P>
The organizers know the spending plan is based on the Salt
Lake Organizing Committee's best assumptions and estimates, and a
lot of unexpected things may happen in the coming years.
</P>
<P>
"We approved the proposal with the caveat that we will
aggressively monitor it," said lan Layton, chairman of the SLOC
board of trustees' budget committee. "We will make no commitments
that we don't have the money to pay for."
</P>
<P>
Layton said the full board will give a vote on October 8 on
his committee's recommendation.
</P>
<P>
Following Thursday's presentation, the proposed budget won
plaudits from members of the United States and International
Olympic committees who sit on SLOC's board.
</P>
<P>
"I'm pleased with the level of detail," said Anita DeFrantz,an
IOC vice president. "We are deeply concerned there is enough to
do the job and this looks like there will be."
</P>
<P>
The proposed spending plan must also be approved by the IOC.
It is more than 400 million dollars larger than the amount
Nagano, Japan, spent to host the Winter Games early this year.
But the Nagano budget didn't include nearly 500 million in
construction costs covered by the government.
</P>
<P>
The Salt Lake spending plan covers 41 functions, such as
medical services or security, 200-plus projects, like the torch
relay, 400 subprojects and 3,000 activities, such as tree plan
tings. 
</P>
</TEXT>
