<HEADLINE> World Donors Pledge $570M to Mozambique </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, September 24 (Xinhua) -- International donors pledged
here Thursday to provide 570 million U.S. Dollars to Mozambique
in 1999 for the country's development.
</P>
<P>
The international partners of Mozambique made the pledge at
the 11th meeting of the Mozambican government's consultative
group.
</P>
<P>
At the just ended two-day meeting, Vice-President of the World
Bank for Africa, Callisto Madavo said the a press conference in
Maputo that the international donors put great trust in the
on-going program implemented by the Mozambican government in
order to eliminate poverty.
</P>
<P>
Many donors have shown their willingness to offer a big sum of
aid, Madavo said. This means that Mozambique's Development
Program for 1999 has won strong support from the donors.
</P>
<P>
The program needs 570 million U.S. Dollars from external help.
</P>
<P>
"I believe that the fund needed by the program will be
guaranteed," said the World Bank official.
</P>
<P>
According to a document issued by the world financial
institution here Thursday evening, the international partners
encourage Mozambique to keep on reforming its public
administration, judiciary and laws, wiping out bureaucratism,
cracking down on corruption and increasing transparency so that
even the poorest population can enjoy the fruits of economic
development.
</P>
<P>
At the workshop, the Mozambican government promised to go
ahead with various reforms.
</P>
<P>
Mozambican Prime Minister Pascoal Mocumbi, together with
several cabinet ministers and the governor of the Mozambique
Central Bank, held talks with the consultative group headed by
Madavo.
</P>
<P>
The consultative group comprise of delegates from 16 countries
and seven international organizations including the World Bank.
</P>
