<HEADLINE> Rushdie Says Odeal Seems to be Over </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 24 (Xinhua) -- Author Salman Rushdie on
Thursday reacted with relief to the news that Iran has dropped its
support for a bounty to be paid for his assassination.
</P>
<P>
"Well, it looks like it is over," Rushdie told Sky Television
outside the Foreign Office after a briefing from government
minister Derek Fatchett.
</P>
<P>
In 1989, Iranian religious leader Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini
pronounced a death sentence on Rushdie for his book The Satanic
Verses and forced him into hiding in Britain ever since.
</P>
<P>
British Foreign Secretary Robin Cook met his Iranian
counterpart, Kamal Kharrazi, at the United Nations in New York
earlier in the day and agreed to upgrade diplomatic ties between
the two countries after Kharrazi said Iran would not threaten
Rushdie's life or encourage anyone else to do so.
</P>
<P>
At the meeting, Kharrazi said his government "has no intention,
nor is it going to take any action whatsoever to threaten the life
of the author of The Satanic Verses...nor will it encourage or
assist anybody to do so."
</P>
<P>
He also said the Iranian government disassociated itself from
any reward that had been offered for the life of Rushdie. An
Iranian revolutionary foundation has placed a $2.5 million bounty
on Rushdie's head.
</P>
<P>
Rushdie said it appeared to him that the lifting of the death
sentence had broad support in Iran.
</P>
<P>
"It seems this has been done in Iran with consensus. There
doesn't seem to be any opposition to it," he said.
</P>
<P>
Iran's decision to settle the Rushdie matter was followed by a
mutual agreement between Iran and Britain to upgrade diplomatic
relations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980925.0264 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UK Managers Complain of Heavy Workload </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 24 (Xinhua) -- British managers at all levels
have cut back on their working week, citing the effect the long
hours culture was having on their personal lives, according to an
Institute of Management (IM) report on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Junior and middle managers were most against long hours, with
nearly 60 percent complaining that they worked long hours either
because it was expected by more senior management, or because they
had no choice.
</P>
<P>
Overall, 78 percent of managers worked more than 40 hours a
week, down from 82 percent last year, while 34 percent (from 38
percent) worked more than 50 hours, Reuters quoted IM as saying.
</P>
<P>
Some 72 percent said working hours affected their relationships
with their partner, with 73 percent saying it encroached on time
spent with their children. That said, 57 percent claimed work was
as important to them as home life.
</P>
<P>
Fewer admitted to working at weekends (34 percent from 41
percent) or during evenings (54 percent from 59 percent).
</P>
<P>
Company restructurings have become a way of life, with 62
percent of managers saying their organization had been reshaped in
the past year.
</P>
<P>
On the upside, these moves were seen by 51 percent as leading
to increased profitability. But restructuring also brought greater
job insecurity (65 percent), lower morale (64 percent), and
reduced motivation and loyalty (49 percent), Reuters said.
</P>
<P>
The results were taken from the second year of an ongoing study
involving 5,000 IM members, of whom 1,312 responded this time, IM
said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980925.0265 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Bank Makes Largest New Loan Commitments in FY 1998 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 24 (Xinhua) -- In the fiscal year 1998,
ended on June 30, the World Bank made the largest new loan
commitments in its history, said the Bank in its annual report
released here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The World Bank's new loan commitments includes 21.1 billion
U.S. dollar loan from the International Bank for Reconstruction
and Development (IBRD), of which 5 billion dollars went to South
Korea and 7.5 billion dollars interest-free credits from the
International Development Association (IDA), up 62 percent over
the previous year.
</P>
<P>
The IBRD/IDA combined disbursements in the year rose to 25.5
billion dollars, up from nearly 20 billion dollars in FY1997.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, the World Bank focused on helping its
member countries manage the social consequences of the economic
and financial crisis by protecting and improving quality of social
services and public expenditures targeted to help the poor. This
included designing and financing social funds and strengthening
social security systems for the elderly and unemployed.
</P>
<P>
The Bank's lending priorities targeted education, health,
nutrition and population as well as the social sector, which
totaled 6.4 billion dollars, and 8.5 billion dollars when the
social protection components of other loans is included. This is
30 percent of total lending, a big increase over 1997 fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
The World Bank responded to the East Asia crisis by pledging
some 16 billion dollars, in addition to its regular lending
program. By the end of the year, 5.65 billion dollars had been
disbursed. A two-pronged, rapid and substantial lending program was
directed both at financial-and corporate-sector restructuring and
preserving social services. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980925.0266 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 6 Zambian Financial Institutions to Share World </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, September 24 (Xinhua)-- The world bank has approved
the participation by six Zambian financial institutions in the
disbursement of its enterprise developement fund.
</P>
<P>
The six institutions including Stanbic Bank, Stanbic Charter
and New Capital Bank will share a loan of 45 million U.S.Dollars,
Minister of Commerce, Trade and Industry David Mpamba said here
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The loan will go to the private export sector of the country.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Zambian government signed here Thursday a
20-million Dollar agreement with the World Food Program (WFP), in
food relief aid, according to Zambia National Broadcasting
Corporation (ZNBC).
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, WFP will provide Zambia with 45,000 tons
of maize as emergency food aid for floods victims in the country.
</P>
</TEXT>
