<HEADLINE> European Stocks Drop with Renewed Fears </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 24 (Xinhua) -- European stocks dropped
Thursday with renewed fears that the financial crises in emerging
markets and the bailout of a major U.S. hedge fund would hurt
corporate earnings.
</P>
<P>
An early bout of excitement at the prospect of a U.S. rate cut
went into reverse by mid-afternoon as Wall Street opened lower.
</P>
<P>
London's FTSE 100 had rallied to a 107 point gain, hitting a
high at 5322.3 in the opening minutes of trade as investors took
heart from the Dow's 257 point rally on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Markets around the world reacted positively to Federal Reserve
Chairman Alan Greenspan's strongest hint yet that U.S. rates could
fall in response to the financial turmoil in international
markets.
</P>
<P>
The Federal Open Markets Committee meets next Tuesday to decide
on policy. U.S. interest rate futures predict a full 50 basis
point cut from 5.50 percent in Fed funds by the end of November.
</P>
<P>
But dealers said that the markets had over-reacted with the
strong rally, which left them open to a bout of of profit-taking.
</P>
<P>
The FTSE 100 ended down 47.1 at 5167.6 after dropping to a low
at 5158.6 as the Dow lost just over 50 points.
</P>
<P>
A 3.5 billion U.S. dollars bailout of U.S. hedge fund Long-Term
Capital, also worried investors.
</P>
<P>
In Frankfurt, German shares fell sharply, too, after a poor
performance in New York and after initial excitement about a
possible U.S. rate cut wore off. The Xetra Dax finished 111.62
points lower at 4611.34.
</P>
<P>
Dealers expected the market to remain quiet on Friday as people
were nervous going into the national election on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Dealers said an earlier indication of the market's fragile
intraday trading was its failure to match last-session gains made
by other major markets.
</P>
<P>
In Paris, shares followed the international trend as Wall
Street turned lower. The Cac 40 finished 42.65 points lower at
3381.13.
</P>
<P>
Some traders were said to be somewhat sceptical about the
possibility of a U.S. rate cut next week.
</P>
<P>
Investor interest was high because Thursday marks the first day
of the new liquidation on the Paris Bourse, dealers said.
</P>
<P>
Investors tend to be more amenable to placing big orders on the
first day of a new trading month after having settled a month's
worth of transactions and cleaned their books. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
