<HEADLINE> Clinton Welcomes Pakistan Nuclear Offer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 24 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill
Clinton Thursday welcomed Pakistan's offer to sign a nuclear test
ban treaty and urged the U.S. Senate to ratify it.
</P>
<P>
"We're very pleased by the statement that the government of
Pakistan has now made with respect to the Comprehensive Test Ban
Treaty," White House spokesman Mike McCurry said.
</P>
<P>
Clinton, noting that two years ago Thursday he became the first
world leader to sign the Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty, urged the
Senate to ratify the convention early next year.
</P>
<P>
Over the past two years, 150 countries have signed the treaty,
including Russia and China, but not India or Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
The treaty bans all nuclear explosions and is meant to
constrain the development of more sophisticated and powerful
nuclear weapons, as well as to limit the spread of nuclear arms
technologies.
</P>
<P>
Opponents in the Republican-controlled Senate say compliance to
the treaty cannot be verified.
</P>
<P>
"The American people understand that Senate approval of the
CTBT is the right thing to do," Clinton said. "I strongly urge the
Senate to give its advice and consent as early as possible next
year."
</P>
<P>
In an address to the opening session of the U.N. General
Assembly on Wednesday, Pakistani Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif said
his country was ready to adhere to the test ban treaty. But he
said it would depend on whether rival India resumed its tests.
</P>
<P>
Clinton made no direct mention of Indian Prime Minister Atal
Bihari Vajpayee's speech to the U.N. General Assembly on Thursday.
Vajpayee said India wanted the treaty to go into force no later
than September 1999.
</P>
<P>
"I look forward to further discussion with the leaders of
Pakistan and India as we emphasize our common obligation to build
peace and security," Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
McCurry said Clinton had not yet decided whether to go ahead
with his plan to visit India and Pakistan in November as part of
an Asia trip, which was put on hold after India and Pakistan
caught the world by surprise by exploding nuclear devices. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
