<HEADLINE> Biotechnology Revolution for 21st Century Agriculture </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 24 (Xinhua) -- An international panel of
experts said here Thursday that there was an urgent need to harness
"biotechnology revolution" to help the poor and protect the
environment in the 21st century and public research should be
provided for all humanity.
</P>
<P>
Scientists predict that biotechnology could contribute to more
food on the same area of land, thereby reducing pressure to expand
into wilderness, rain forest or marginal lands that support
biodiversity and vital ecosystem services.
</P>
<P>
It could reduce post-harvest loss of food and improve the
quality of fresh and processed foods, thus boosting the "realized
nutritional yield" per hectare.
</P>
<P>
It also could displace resource -- and energy -- intensive
inputs, such as fuel, fertilizers or pesticides, thus reducing
unintended impacts on the environment.
</P>
<P>
Such new scientific opportunities need a unique leadership
effort to be mobilized and provided to the regions that need them
urgently to feed their growing population, noted the panel, which
assessed the work of the Consultative Group on International
Agricultural Research (CGIAR).
</P>
<P>
The CGIAR, founded in 1971, consists of 16 international
agricultural research centers around the world, most in developing
countries, and was backed by the Food And Agriculture Organization
of the United Nations, the U.N. Development Program and the World
Bank.
</P>
<P>
Productivity and natural resource management are the twin
pillars of CGIAR research on aquatic resources, biodiversity, food
crops, forestry and agro-forestry, livestock, soil and water
nutrients, water management, and agriculture-related policies.
</P>
<P>
Noting that the CGIAR was one of the best organizations to
serve the developing countries in the agricultural research, panel
chairman Maurice Strong said at a press briefing that global food
security looms as society's largest challenge as we enter the next
century. "Through its science and experience, the CGIAR can
contribute to the solution of this problem."
</P>
<P>
The panel said scientific revolution taking place in biology
and information technology are a major cause for optimism. But a
strong research system like CGIAR is needed to form the scientific
and institutional linkages necessary for ensuring that the poor
will benefit from the cutting-edge science.
</P>
<P>
It suggested the CGIAR adjust its strategy to take full
advantage of opportunities in integrated gene management,
integrated natural resource management and information technology.
</P>
<P>
It also recommended the CGIAR establish a global network for
integrated natural resources management to link productivity
research with environmentally-sound management of the eath's
natural resources. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
